        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Atok is a small Benguet town an hour north of Baguio along the Halsema Highway. Most travelers never get past Baguio proper, which is the reason Atok still feels like a quiet mountain town. The road climbs past pine forest and vegetable terraces, and the air at 2,200 meters above sea level is the coldest you will get in mainland Luzon without sleeping in a tent.</p>
<p>This is a one-day DIY route that strings together the three flower farms, one viewpoint, and one carinderia stop. Tara, the kwento starts at the Baguio jeepney terminal.</p>
<h2>How to Get to Atok</h2>
<p>From Baguio, walk to the Slaughterhouse Compound jeepney terminal in Magsaysay. Jeepneys to Buguias, Mankayan, and Sagada pass through Atok and drop off at the marker for whichever farm you ask the driver to stop at. The fare to the Northern Blossom turn-off is around 100 to 150 pesos. Trip time is one hour to one hour twenty.</p>
<p>If you are with a barkada, a van rental from Baguio is faster and lets you do all three farms without waiting for the next jeepney. Drivers know the route well.</p>
<h2>Northern Blossom Flower Farm</h2>
<p>This is the famous one, the place that went viral in 2018 for the carpets of cabbage roses and the highland greens stacked against a sea of clouds. The farm sits at 2,200 meters and the temperature drops to 12 to 14 degrees Celsius even at midday in December and January. Entrance is around 200 pesos and the staff hand you a small map of the trail loops.</p>
<p>The trick is to go early. The fog rolls in by 10:30 a.m. on most days and the photos turn flat. Open hours start at 6:00 a.m. on weekends. Mondays and Tuesdays are the quietest visiting days. Bring a light jacket; the wind on the ridges is real.</p>
<h2>Haight's Place (Sakura Garden)</h2>
<p>Haight's is the one with the cherry blossom trees. The sakura bloom in late January through mid-February in a normal year. Outside the bloom window, the garden is still a pleasant stop for the small cafe and the bonsai displays. Entrance is modest, around 100 pesos.</p>
<p>Set expectations for the sakura. The trees are real Japanese cherry blossoms planted by the family, and the bloom is small compared to a Japanese park. Manage expectations and you will not be disappointed. The garden cafe serves a decent strawberry shortcake and hot chocolate, both sulit after a cold morning walk.</p>
<h2>Sakura Park (Atok)</h2>
<p>The local government planted a second sakura park along the highway a few kilometers from Haight's. It is free to enter, smaller, and the bloom window is the same late January window. The fence is low and the view of the surrounding mountains is open.</p>
<p>If you are short on time, pick either Haight's or the public Sakura Park, not both. They cover the same trees with slightly different settings.</p>
<h2>Mt Timbak Viewpoint</h2>
<p>Mt Timbak is the third-highest peak in Luzon at 2,717 meters. The viewpoint at the highway pull-out is free and the photo is the one with the cross at the summit and the road snaking below. The summit cross is a 30-minute walk up from the highway and the ridge is exposed; do this on a clear morning before the fog rolls in.</p>
<p>From the cross you can see the whole Halsema chain and on the clearest days the South China Sea is a faint blue line on the horizon. The Igorot communities have small carinderias near the pull-out for hot coffee and pandesal.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat</h2>
<p>The carinderias along the Halsema serve rice meals for 80 to 120 pesos. Order the mountain rice with whatever ulam is in the steam tray; the pinakbet and the fried tilapia are usually fresh. Coffee is local Benguet arabica and the cup is hot. Strawberry vendors sell along the road in season (December to April).</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through February is the cold-and-clear season. Sakura bloom is late January to mid-February. March and April are warmer but the sky stays clear. May through August is the rainy season and the fog cuts visibility for most of the day. Avoid Saturdays in February; Northern Blossom fills up by 8 a.m. on those weekends.</p>
<p>Atok is the rare Cordillera day trip that delivers a real change of climate without an overnight stay. One full day from Baguio covers the three farms and the Timbak viewpoint, and you are back in the city by sunset.</p>
