        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Mt Timbak sits at 2,717 meters above sea level in Atok, Benguet. It is the third-highest peak in Luzon after Mt Pulag and Mt Tabayoc, and the only one of the three that you can reach by jeepney from Baguio in under two hours. The summit walk from the trailhead is 30 minutes on a paved road, which is why some climbers call it a tourist summit. For the patient traveler, the climb is short and the view is real.</p>
<p>This is a one-day DIY guide. Tara, the kwento starts at the Halsema Highway pull-out.</p>
<h2>How to Get There</h2>
<p>From Baguio, take the Slaughterhouse Compound jeepney terminal in Magsaysay. Board any jeepney heading to Buguias, Mankayan, or Sagada and tell the driver "Timbak summit." Fare is around 150 pesos. The ride is one hour to one hour fifteen minutes. The jeep drops you at a small marker along the highway and the road up is on your right.</p>
<p>Return jeepneys pass every 30 to 45 minutes until late afternoon. The last reliable one back to Baguio is around 4 p.m.; after that you risk waiting in the cold dark.</p>
<h2>The Walk Up</h2>
<p>From the highway the road climbs a paved switchback for about 1.5 kilometers. Walking time is 25 to 35 minutes depending on pace. The grade is steady but never harsh. The ridge is exposed to the wind so a light jacket is mandatory even at midday.</p>
<p>The summit is marked by a large cross and three smaller mummies caves below the road. The caves are not always open to the public; ask the local caretaker. On a clear day the 360-degree view covers the Halsema chain, Mt Pulag in the distance, and on the rare clear morning the South China Sea is a faint blue line to the west.</p>
<h2>The Timbak Mummies</h2>
<p>The Igorot fire-cured mummies are part of the cultural heritage of Atok. The caves are below the summit cross along a steep side trail. Entry is by donation, around 50 to 100 pesos, and a local guide will explain the burial practice. Photos are not allowed inside the cave; respect the rule, the mummies are ancestors of the families that still live in the valley.</p>
<h2>Camping at the Summit</h2>
<p>Camping is allowed near the cross and there is a small flat area below the summit suited to two or three tents. Bring a four-season tent if you can; the wind at 2,700 meters in December can drop the chill factor to single digits. The nearest water source is at the small sari-sari store at the road junction below the summit, so carry your drinking water up.</p>
<p>Sunset and sunrise are the reasons to camp. The sea of clouds rolls below the ridge on most cold-season mornings and the photo is one you will keep. The Milky Way is visible on moonless nights when the sky is clear.</p>
<h2>Trail Variant: The Long Way</h2>
<p>If you want a real hike, ask the locals about the trail from Sinipsip village that climbs through pine forest and vegetable terraces for about three hours to the summit. The trail starts at a barangay road junction along the Halsema. A local guide is recommended; the trail is unmarked and crosses farm parcels.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<p>Trail runners or hiking shoes are fine on the paved summit road. The Sinipsip trail variant needs proper hiking boots. Bring a beanie and gloves in December and January; the temperature at the summit drops to 5 to 8 degrees Celsius at dawn. Carry your trash down; the local Igorot community manages the summit area on a small budget and your trash is theirs to deal with.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through February is the cold-and-clear window with the highest chance of a sea of clouds. March through May is warmer but the haze cuts visibility. June through October is the rainy season; the road is passable but the summit is in cloud most days.</p>
<p>Mt Timbak is the rare Luzon summit that gives you a high-altitude view without a multi-day climb. Pair it with the Atok flower farms and you have a full day above 2,000 meters.</p>
