        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Northern Blossom Flower Farm sits at 2,200 meters above sea level in Sayangan, Atok, Benguet. The farm went viral in 2018 for the carpets of cabbage roses, the highland greens stacked in raised beds, and the sea of clouds that rolls below the ridges most cold-season mornings. Eight years on, the farm is still family-run and the experience is still the same calm cold-morning walk that earned the early Instagram posts.</p>
<p>This is a slow read, not an itinerary. Tara, here is what the cold morning is actually like.</p>
<h2>Getting In</h2>
<p>From Baguio, jeepneys leave the Slaughterhouse Compound terminal in Magsaysay throughout the morning. Tell the driver "Northern Blossom" or "Sayangan, Atok." Fare is 100 to 150 pesos. Travel time is one hour to one hour fifteen minutes. The jeep drops you at the highway marker and the farm gate is a five-minute walk on a side road.</p>
<p>If you are based in Manila and you can leave on a 4 a.m. bus, you can be at the farm by 10 a.m., but the fog usually wins by then. A Baguio overnight followed by an early jeepney is the sulit plan.</p>
<h2>Entrance and Layout</h2>
<p>Entrance is around 200 pesos per person. The farm hands you a printed map of the three short trail loops: the upper terrace with the cabbage roses, the middle terrace with the lettuce and broccoli rows, and the lower terrace with the small bonsai garden. Each loop is 10 to 15 minutes of slow walking.</p>
<p>There is a small canteen near the entrance serving hot chocolate, brewed Benguet coffee, and instant noodles. Order the hot chocolate. The hands warm up around the cup and the canteen window faces the cloud line.</p>
<h2>The Cabbage Roses</h2>
<p>The cabbage roses are the headline crop. They are a hybrid that looks like a giant ornamental cabbage with leaves that range from deep magenta to pale green. The rows are arranged in concentric rings, and the staff ask visitors to walk on the grass paths between rows rather than between plants. The rule is fair and the photos are better from the paths anyway.</p>
<h2>The Cloud Line</h2>
<p>The reason to come early is the sea of clouds. On a normal December morning the clouds fill the valley below the farm and the upper ridges rise above. The cloud line burns off between 10 and 11 a.m. on a sunny day. On a cloudy day the farm itself is inside the cloud and the photos are flat. The forecast for Buguias is a better predictor than the Baguio forecast; check both the night before.</p>
<h2>What to Wear</h2>
<p>December and January mornings hit 8 to 12 degrees Celsius at the farm. A light fleece and a windbreaker are enough; a heavy jacket is overkill. Closed shoes are mandatory; the paths are damp and the mud sticks to canvas sneakers. Bring a hat if you are sensitive to the sun; the UV at 2,200 meters is strong even at 8 a.m.</p>
<h2>The Carinderia Stop</h2>
<p>After the farm, walk back to the highway and try the small carinderia at the Sayangan junction. Order the rice meal with whatever is in the steam tray. The pinakbet with mountain vegetables and the fried tilapia are usually fresh. A meal is around 90 to 120 pesos and the canteen is warm.</p>
<h2>What to Skip</h2>
<p>Skip the farm on Saturdays in February. Skip the farm in the rainy season unless you accept that the photos may not happen. Skip the farm if you are looking for a Korea-Japan style flower park; this is a working highland farm and the rows are real produce, not display beds.</p>
<h2>The Honest Read</h2>
<p>Northern Blossom is one of the few Philippine destinations where the experience is exactly what the photos promise, as long as you come early and you come in the dry-cold season. The farm is small, the walk is short, and the air is the coldest you will breathe in mainland Luzon. Sulit for the patient traveler who books the jeepney early and dresses for the cold.</p>
