        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Mt Kalugong sits at 1,800 meters above sea level in La Trinidad, Benguet. It is a small family-run eco park with a 20-minute trail to the summit, a cluster of limestone formations near the top, and a view of the Strawberry Farm valley spread out below. The whole visit fits inside a half-day from Baguio and the climb is gentle enough for first-time walkers.</p>
<p>This is a calm half-day read. Tara, the kwento starts at the Baguio jeepney terminal.</p>
<h2>How to Get There</h2>
<p>From Baguio, take a jeepney from the Magsaysay area marked for La Trinidad and ask the driver to drop you at the Mt Kalugong turn-off in Tawang. Fare is around 15 to 20 pesos. From the turn-off, a short habal-habal ride or a 20-minute uphill walk brings you to the park entrance. The road is paved but steep in the last stretch.</p>
<p>Open hours are 5:30 a.m. to 5:30 p.m. and the entrance fee is around 100 pesos for adults. Morning visits beat the afternoon haze.</p>
<h2>The Trail Up</h2>
<p>The summit trail is a wide gravel path with stone steps in the steeper sections. Walking time is 15 to 25 minutes at a slow pace. The grade is gentle and the trail is shaded by pines for most of the climb. The trail is suitable for kids, elders, and first-time hikers; trail runners are fine.</p>
<p>Near the top the trail opens up into a clearing with limestone outcrops that look like small standing stones. The locals call the formation the "Cordillera Stonehenge," though the comparison is loose. The rocks are still photogenic at sunrise and the surrounding pines frame the view.</p>
<h2>The Strawberry Valley View</h2>
<p>From the summit clearing you can see the whole La Trinidad valley spread out below. The strawberry farm rows are the geometric pattern in the foreground, the city of Baguio is the small ridge to the south, and the Cordillera mountains stretch to the north. On a clear winter morning the air is still and the valley fills with a thin layer of fog that lifts by 8 a.m.</p>
<h2>The Pine Forest Loop</h2>
<p>The park has a secondary trail loop through the pine forest behind the limestone clearing. The loop adds 30 to 40 minutes to the visit and circles a small open meadow with native ground orchids in season (March to May). The trail is well marked and rangers patrol the area on weekends.</p>
<h2>The Cafe and Camping Ground</h2>
<p>The park has a small cafe near the entrance with hot drinks, snacks, and a few rice meals. The cafe deck faces the valley and the morning view is the same one the summit clearing has, minus the climb. There is also a small camping ground with tent pads for overnight stays; the rate is around 200 pesos per pitch plus the entrance fee.</p>
<p>The camping ground is the quiet alternative to the busier Camp John Hay grounds. The temperature drops to 12 to 15 degrees Celsius on December nights; bring a warm sleeping bag.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<p>A light jacket, closed walking shoes, drinking water, a small snack. The trail has no water source. The park sells bottled water at the entrance but the price is double the city price. Bring trash bags; carry out everything you bring in.</p>
<h2>Pair It With</h2>
<p>The strawberry farm valley is a 10-minute jeepney ride from the Kalugong turn-off. After the morning hike, pair the visit with a strawberry-picking session at the La Trinidad farm or a coffee stop at one of the Baguio cafes. The combined half-day fits a slow Sunday plan.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through February is the cold, clear, and quiet window. March through May is warmer with bigger crowds (school break). June through October is the rainy season; the trail is muddy and the view is in fog most days.</p>
<p>Mt Kalugong is the calm option for travelers who want a Cordillera summit without the early-morning Pulag drive. Sulit for a slow half-day from Baguio.</p>
