        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Marlboro Country is the name locals gave to a grassy hill above Sagada town, said to be inspired by the old Marlboro cigarette ads of cowboys riding on open plains. The ridge sits at around 1,700 meters and the trail loops past St. Mary's Episcopal Church, the public cemetery, the hanging coffins of Echo Valley, and the small Bokong waterfall before climbing to the open ridge above the town.</p>
<p>This is a calm three- to four-hour loop. Tara, here is the kwento.</p>
<h2>The Starting Point</h2>
<p>The loop starts at the Sagada Tourism Information Center along the main road. Register, pay the environmental fee (around 100 pesos), and hire a local guide. A guide is mandatory for the Echo Valley section and the rate is fixed by the local government at 600 to 800 pesos for the half-day loop.</p>
<p>From the office, walk five minutes to St. Mary's Episcopal Church. The church was built by the American Episcopal mission in 1904 and the stone walls still hold up. The graveyard behind the church is the entrance to the Echo Valley trail.</p>
<h2>Echo Valley and the Hanging Coffins</h2>
<p>The Echo Valley trail descends through a pine forest along a marked path. The hanging coffins are visible from a viewpoint above the cliff face; the coffins are the carved wooden burial boxes attached to the limestone wall, a practice still observed by some Igorot families today. Show respect; do not point, do not climb the cliff, do not pose with the coffins.</p>
<p>The valley earned the name "Echo" because shouts bounce off the cliff walls. The local guides sometimes call out the names of the dead as part of the small cultural sharing.</p>
<h2>Bokong Falls</h2>
<p>From Echo Valley the trail climbs through a small ravine to Bokong Falls. The falls are a small 10-meter cascade with a shallow pool at the base. The water is cold even at midday. The pool is large enough for a quick dip and the cliffs around it provide shade.</p>
<p>The trail to Bokong is muddy in the rainy season; trail runners or hiking shoes are recommended over canvas sneakers.</p>
<h2>The Climb to Marlboro Country</h2>
<p>From Bokong the trail climbs up a series of switchbacks through the pine forest to the grassy ridge. The climb is the steepest section of the loop and takes 45 minutes to one hour at a slow pace. The ridge opens up into a wide grass field with scattered cattle and a view of the surrounding valleys.</p>
<p>The "Marlboro" comparison is to the cattle and the open grass; the photo with the cattle silhouetted against the morning fog is the iconic one.</p>
<h2>The Sunrise Window</h2>
<p>For the sea of clouds at sunrise, you need to leave the Tourism Center at 4 a.m. with a guide and a headlamp. The climb in the dark adds a level of difficulty but the reward is the unobstructed view of the cloud-filled valleys below the ridge. Sunrise window is 5:45 to 6:15 a.m. depending on the season.</p>
<p>If a 4 a.m. start is not your speed, do the loop in the late morning. The cloud cover is usually gone by 8 a.m. but the ridge view is still wide and the walk is calmer in the late light.</p>
<h2>The Walk Back</h2>
<p>From the ridge, the loop descends through a different trail back to the town center. Total walking time for the full loop (church, Echo Valley, Bokong, Marlboro, back) is three to four hours at a slow pace. The walk back drops you off at the bottom of the main road, a five-minute walk from the Tourism Center.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<p>Hiking shoes or trail runners, a light jacket, drinking water, a small snack. The trail has no water source between Bokong and the ridge. A headlamp if you are doing the sunrise start. A trash bag; carry out everything.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>November through February is the cold, clear, and dry window. The sea of clouds is most reliable in December and January. March through May is warm with afternoon haze. June through October is the rainy season; the trail is slippery and the ridge is often in fog.</p>
<p>Marlboro Country is the slow alternative to the closed-off Kiltepan Peak. Sulit for the patient traveler who wakes up early or walks slow in the late morning.</p>
