    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 7. BAGUIO TO SAGADA BUS THE GL TRANS HONEST GUIDE
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://wanderera.com/baguio-to-sagada/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Wander Era',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Baguio to Sagada by Bus: The GL Trans Honest Guide',
        'slug' => 'baguio-to-sagada-bus-gl-trans-honest-guide',
        'excerpt' => 'Baguio to Sagada is a six-hour climb along the Halsema. Here is the honest read on the GL Trans bus, the schedule, and what to expect.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>The bus from Baguio to Sagada is one of the longer, slower rides in Luzon. The distance is 150 kilometers but the road is the Halsema Highway, a winding mountain road that climbs from 1,500 meters in Baguio to 2,200 at the highest pass before dropping to Sagada at 1,500. The trip takes five to six hours and the bus stops at every town along the way.</p>
<p>This is the honest read for first-time travelers. Tara, here is the kwento.</p>
<h2>The Operator: GL Trans</h2>
<p>GL Trans (also called Lizardo Trans) is the main operator between Baguio and Sagada. The buses are non-air-conditioned, with windows that open and a small luggage rack on top. The seats are basic but the leg room is decent. There is no toilet on board.</p>
<p>A second operator, D'Rising Sun, runs on a parallel schedule with similar buses. Either is fine; whichever leaves next is the one to take.</p>
<h2>The Terminal</h2>
<p>The GL Trans terminal is at Dangwa, in the Magsaysay area of Baguio. From Burnham Park, a 10-minute walk or a quick taxi ride. From the Victory Liner terminal (where most Manila buses arrive), a five-minute taxi ride.</p>
<p>There is no online booking. Walk in, buy a ticket, board. On peak weekends (long weekends, December, summer break) arrive an hour before departure to get a seat.</p>
<h2>The Schedule</h2>
<p>GL Trans runs hourly departures from Baguio to Sagada between 6 a.m. and 1 p.m. The last reliable departure is 1 p.m.; after that you arrive in Sagada after dark. Return trips from Sagada to Baguio run on the same hourly schedule.</p>
<p>Fare is around 250 to 300 pesos one way. Pay in cash on the bus or at the terminal counter.</p>
<h2>The Ride</h2>
<p>The first hour climbs out of Baguio through La Trinidad and Tublay. The road is paved but narrow and the bus stops for pickup at every barangay. The next two hours cross the Halsema highest pass through Atok and Buguias; this is where the air thins and your ears pop. The last hour drops into Bontoc and crosses the Chico River before climbing back up to Sagada.</p>
<p>The ride is bumpy. If you are prone to motion sickness, take a dimenhydrinate (Bonamine) 30 minutes before departure. Sit on the left side of the bus for the cleaner cliff views; sit on the right if you want to see the vegetable terraces and Sayangan farms.</p>
<h2>The Toilet Stops</h2>
<p>GL Trans makes two scheduled toilet stops: one at the Sayangan junction in Atok (around 1.5 hours in) and one at the Bontoc terminal (around 4 hours in). The Sayangan stop is 10 minutes; the Bontoc stop is 15 to 20 minutes and the bus changes drivers there.</p>
<p>Use the Bontoc stop for a quick rice meal at the carinderia next to the terminal; the bus does not stop for food after Bontoc.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<p>A small bag of snacks, a one-liter water bottle, a light jacket (the bus crosses 2,200 meters and the wind is real), a face mask if you are sensitive to dust, a small pillow if you can sleep on transit. A book or downloaded podcasts for the long stretches without signal.</p>
<h2>What to Expect on Arrival</h2>
<p>The bus drops you at the Sagada Tourism Information Center along the main road. Register at the office and pay the environmental fee (around 100 pesos). The town inns are within walking distance; the longest walk is 15 minutes.</p>
<p>If you arrive after 4 p.m. the registration office is still open until 7 p.m., but the kitchens at most inns close by 8 p.m., so eat dinner soon after you check in.</p>
<h2>The Return</h2>
<p>The last return bus to Baguio leaves Sagada at 1 p.m. Plan your activities for the morning of departure day; do not book a 9 a.m. trip and a 1 p.m. bus on the same day.</p>
<p>Baguio to Sagada is the slow road; it is the kind of trip where you read a book, doze off, and arrive in a town that still feels like a town. Sulit for the patient traveler.</p>
