    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 10. PAMUAYAN WATERFALL PORT BARTON TRAIL
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://wanderera.com/how-to-get-to-paumayan-waterfall/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Wander Era',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Pamuayan Waterfall, Port Barton: A Quiet Trail Day',
        'slug' => 'pamuayan-waterfall-port-barton-quiet-trail-day',
        'excerpt' => 'Pamuayan Falls sits a 45-minute walk from Port Barton along a forest trail. Here is the calm read on the half-day visit.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Pamuayan Waterfall sits in the forested hills behind Port Barton in northern Palawan. The falls are reached by a 45-minute walk from the town through palm plantations, river crossings, and a short jungle stretch. Most travelers do the island-hopping in Port Barton and skip the inland walk, which is exactly why the trail to Pamuayan is still quiet.</p>
<p>This is a calm half-day read. Tara, the kwento starts at the Port Barton beach.</p>
<h2>How to Get to the Trailhead</h2>
<p>From the main beach in Port Barton, walk north along the dirt road past the local school for about 15 minutes until you reach a small bridge over the Pamuayan River. The trail to the falls starts on the right side of the bridge and follows the river upstream.</p>
<p>You can also take a tricycle from the town center to the bridge for around 50 pesos; the ride saves 15 minutes of walking on a hot day.</p>
<h2>The Trail</h2>
<p>The trail is a single-track path along the river through palm plantations and second-growth forest. There are three to four river crossings depending on the season; in the dry season the crossings are ankle-deep and the rocks are exposed, in the rainy season the crossings are knee-deep and the rocks are slippery.</p>
<p>Walking time from the bridge to the falls is 30 to 45 minutes at a slow pace. The grade is gentle and the shade is generous. Trail runners or water sandals are the right footwear.</p>
<h2>The Falls</h2>
<p>Pamuayan is a 15-meter waterfall that drops into a wide swimming pool ringed by limestone boulders. The pool is around two to three meters deep at the center and the water is cold even at midday. The cliff above the falls is a small jumping platform for the brave (4 to 5 meters; check the depth first).</p>
<p>The pool is large enough for 10 to 15 people without crowding. On most weekdays you will be alone or with one other small group; on weekends in March to May you might share with five to ten others.</p>
<h2>The Side Pool</h2>
<p>Downstream of the main pool there is a smaller second pool with a shallower depth (one to 1.5 meters) and a flatter bottom. This is the kids' pool and the calmer option for non-swimmers. The two pools are connected by a small chute that you can slide down.</p>
<h2>The Honest Read on Fees</h2>
<p>There is no formal entrance fee at the falls. Some small enterprises along the trail (a sari-sari store at the trailhead, a local family at the second river crossing) offer drinks and snacks for sale and a few collect a small donation (20 to 50 pesos) for trail maintenance. Pay the donation; the locals maintain the trail and the small wooden bridges on a small budget.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<p>Swim clothes, a quick-dry towel, a small dry bag for valuables, drinking water (one liter per person), insect repellent (the river crossings have mosquitoes), and a small snack. Hat and sunglasses for the walk; the trail is shaded but the open sections near the bridge are hot.</p>
<h2>The Return Walk</h2>
<p>The walk back follows the same trail. Total time on the trail (out, swim, back) is two and a half to three hours. Plan to be back in town by mid-afternoon for a late lunch and a calm beach sunset.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry, warm window. The water in the falls is lower in March and April but still swimmable. June through October is the rainy season; the river crossings become harder and the trail is muddy. The falls are at their fullest in September after the heaviest rains.</p>
<h2>Pair It With</h2>
<p>Pair the Pamuayan walk with a late-afternoon beach swim at the main Port Barton beach, or with a sunset banca ride to the small island sandbar just offshore. The combined day is a calm one and the kwento with the barkada over dinner is sulit.</p>
<p>Pamuayan is the slow alternative to the busier island-hopping circuit. Sulit for the patient traveler who wants to walk somewhere quiet in Palawan.</p>
