    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 11. PORT BARTON SLOW WEEKEND THREE-ISLAND ROUTE
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://wanderera.com/things-to-do-in-port-barton/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Wander Era',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Port Barton Three-Island Slow Weekend, Palawan',
        'slug' => 'port-barton-three-island-slow-weekend-palawan',
        'excerpt' => 'Port Barton is the slower Palawan base between Puerto Princesa and El Nido. Here is the calm three-island weekend route.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Port Barton is a small fishing village on the western coast of northern Palawan, about three to four hours by van from Puerto Princesa or El Nido. The bay is sheltered, the beach is a kilometer of warm sand, and the offshore islands are still uncrowded compared to El Nido or Coron. The town has one main road, a small carinderia strip, and a calm pace that the surrounding islands match.</p>
<p>This is a slow three-day weekend route. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>Day One: Arrive and Walk the Bay</h2>
<p>Vans from Puerto Princesa leave San Jose terminal hourly between 6 a.m. and 1 p.m. Fare is around 500 pesos and the trip is three to three and a half hours on a paved road. Vans from El Nido follow a similar schedule for a four-hour trip.</p>
<p>Arrive in Port Barton by early afternoon. The main road runs parallel to the beach for about 800 meters and the inn cluster is along this stretch. Walk the full beach end to end (around 30 minutes) to get a sense of the town. Stop at one of the small carinderias for a late lunch; the grilled tuna with rice and a cold buko juice is the standard order. End the day with a sunset on the beach; the bay faces west so the sun sets directly over the water.</p>
<h2>Day Two: The Three-Island Tour (Tour A)</h2>
<p>The standard Port Barton boat tour is called Tour A and covers three islands plus two snorkel stops in a full day. The boat leaves around 9 a.m. and returns by 4 p.m. Rate is around 1,200 to 1,500 pesos per person on a shared banca with five to eight other travelers.</p>
<p>The first stop is the German Island for a swim and a coconut break. The second stop is Exotic Island for snorkeling at a coral garden with abundant fish. The third stop is Paradise Island for lunch (grilled fish, rice, and fresh fruit). The fourth stop is the starfish sanctuary where dozens of orange and red starfish are visible at shallow depths. The fifth stop is the snorkel point at Aquarium Reef.</p>
<p>The boat operators rotate the route depending on tide and weather; ask which version you are getting before paying. The standard route is calm and the snorkel stops are well-coordinated.</p>
<h2>Day Three: Pamuayan Falls and a Slow Lunch</h2>
<p>The third day is the inland day. Walk to the bridge at the edge of town and take the 45-minute trail to Pamuayan Falls. Swim, walk back, eat a slow lunch at one of the beachfront restaurants, and catch the 1 p.m. van back to Puerto Princesa or the 2 p.m. van to El Nido.</p>
<p>If you have a fourth day, do the Tour B boat tour instead of the falls. Tour B covers the long beach at Inaladelan Island and the local pearl farm; the route is longer (sometimes 7 to 8 hours) and the snorkel stops are deeper.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat</h2>
<p>Tia Lola's serves the best Italian pizza in town; the wood-fired oven is real and the dough is hand-stretched. Gacayan's is the local carinderia with the cheapest grilled fish and rice meals (around 150 pesos). Greenviews has a quiet garden setting and a small Filipino menu. For breakfast, Ausan Beach Front Cafe serves a decent Filipino breakfast and brewed coffee.</p>
<h2>The Electricity Notice</h2>
<p>Port Barton runs on a small barangay generator and the power is on a fixed schedule (usually 5 p.m. to 11 p.m. with occasional outages). Some inns have private generators that run longer. Charge devices in the evening and bring a power bank for the afternoon. The wifi is spotty across the town.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry, calm window with the clearest snorkel water. June through October is the rainy season; the boat tours run on most days but the visibility drops and the wind picks up. Avoid the long weekends (Holy Week, Labor Day, Independence Day); the small town fills up and the boats are booked solid.</p>
<p>Port Barton is the calm Palawan base for travelers who want the islands without the El Nido crowds. Sulit for the patient traveler who likes a slower bay and a quieter town.</p>
