    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 12. EL NIDO TO CORON MULTI-DAY BOAT EXPEDITION
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://wanderera.com/boat-tour-expedition-between-el-nido-and-coron/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Wander Era',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'El Nido to Coron Multi-Day Boat Expedition: A Calm Read',
        'slug' => 'el-nido-coron-multi-day-boat-expedition-calm-read',
        'excerpt' => 'The El Nido to Coron multi-day boat expedition is a four-day camping cruise through northern Palawan. Here is the slow honest read.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>The El Nido to Coron multi-day boat expedition is a four-day, three-night camping cruise through the islands of northern Palawan. The route covers around 150 kilometers of open water and a chain of small islands, hidden beaches, and snorkeling stops that you cannot reach on a day trip from either El Nido or Coron. The operators are a small group of dedicated outfitters (Tao Philippines, Big Dream Boatman, Buhay Isla, and a few others) and the experience is intentionally slow.</p>
<p>This is a calm read on what the trip is actually like. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>The Boats</h2>
<p>The expedition boats are traditional bancas with a small kitchen, a covered dining deck, and a flat sleeping deck for the crew. Passengers sleep on the beach in tents or small beach huts each night, not on the boat. The capacity is small (16 to 24 passengers depending on the operator) and the boats run with a crew of six to eight.</p>
<h2>The Route</h2>
<p>The standard route starts in El Nido and ends in Coron (or vice versa) and covers around 12 to 15 island stops over four days. The exact stops change based on the weather and the tide, but the typical sequence includes Cadlao Island, the Linapacan group (Nangalao, Cabuli, and a few small uninhabited cays), the Black Island area, and the small islands south of Culion.</p>
<p>Each day includes two to three island stops for swimming, snorkeling, and a beach lunch cooked by the crew. The cruising time between stops is one to three hours.</p>
<h2>The Camping</h2>
<p>Nights are spent on small beach camps run by the operators in partnership with local families. The camps have basic facilities: a covered dining area, fresh water for bathing, a composting toilet, and a small kitchen. Sleeping is in tents (provided) on the sand or in small thatched beach huts. There is no electricity; the camps run on small solar lanterns.</p>
<p>The simple camping is the point of the trip. If you need wifi, air conditioning, and a private bathroom, the expedition is not the right format.</p>
<h2>The Food</h2>
<p>The crew cooks all meals on board or at the beach camps. The menu is fresh fish, rice, local vegetables, and a few Filipino classics like adobo and sinigang. Breakfast is the standard tapsilog or longganisa with rice. The food is one of the best parts of the trip; the fish is bought from the small fishing villages along the route.</p>
<h2>The Snorkeling</h2>
<p>The snorkeling stops are the headline experience. The Linapacan strait between El Nido and Coron has some of the clearest water in the Philippines, with visibility regularly hitting 30 to 40 meters. The reefs are alive with corals, schools of small reef fish, and the occasional turtle. Bring your own mask and snorkel if you have one; the rental sets on board are basic.</p>
<h2>The Honest Read on the Cost</h2>
<p>The expedition is the most expensive way to see northern Palawan and the rate is intentional. The fee covers food, fuel, crew, camp fees, and the small contributions to the local communities along the route. The operators do not run on a price-cutting margin; the small-group format and the camp arrangement do not scale. Expect to pay several times the cost of a regular day tour.</p>
<h2>The Departure Days</h2>
<p>The expedition runs on a fixed schedule (usually two to three departures per week per operator) and bookings fill up weeks in advance during the high season (December to May). Book at least four to six weeks ahead; the small boats do not have spare slots in February or March.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<p>Quick-dry clothes, a swimsuit, a light sleeping liner (the tents have basic bedding), a headlamp, a power bank, reef-safe sunscreen, a small dry bag for valuables, and a book or notebook. The camps have no charging stations; bring two power banks for a four-day trip. Cash for tips and small purchases at the local villages.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry, calm window with the clearest snorkel water and the smoothest sea. June through October is the rainy season and most operators pause the expedition. The peak months are February and March; the shoulder months of December, January, April, and May are calmer and cheaper.</p>
<p>The El Nido to Coron expedition is the slow Palawan trip that you remember for years. Sulit for the patient traveler who books early and accepts the simple camping.</p>
