    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 13. CORON OR EL NIDO CHOOSING YOUR PALAWAN BASE
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://wanderera.com/coron-vs-el-nido/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Wander Era',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Coron or El Nido: Choosing Your Palawan Base',
        'slug' => 'coron-or-el-nido-choosing-palawan-base',
        'excerpt' => 'Coron and El Nido are both in northern Palawan but the two trips are not the same. Here is the calm honest pick.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Coron and El Nido are both in northern Palawan and both run popular boat tours through limestone islands and clear lagoons. First-time travelers often pick one based on a single viral photo; experienced travelers pick based on the kind of trip they actually want.</p>
<p>This is a calm honest pick. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>The Geography</h2>
<p>Coron is the town on Busuanga Island, with the famous tours running to nearby Coron Island, Culion, and the small cays of the Calamian group. El Nido is the town on the mainland tip of Palawan, with the famous tours running to the Bacuit Bay islands, the lagoons of Miniloc, and the cliffs of Pinasil and Helicopter Islands.</p>
<p>The two are 200 kilometers apart by water and there is no road between them. You connect by ferry (eight hours), by the expedition cruise (four days), or by a short flight via Manila or Cebu.</p>
<h2>The Vibe</h2>
<p>Coron town is a fishing town with a small main road, a busy market, and an emerging tourist strip. The boats leave from the town pier and the islands are 20 to 45 minutes away. The town has a working-class feel and the restaurants and inns are concentrated in a small grid.</p>
<p>El Nido town is a more developed tourist strip with a long beach lined by hotels, restaurants, bars, and dive shops. The boats leave from the main beach and the islands are 30 to 60 minutes away. The town is louder, busier, and more expensive.</p>
<h2>The Boat Tours</h2>
<p>Coron's signature tour is Tour A, which covers Kayangan Lake (the famous freshwater lake inside Coron Island), the Twin Lagoon (where you swim or kayak from a cool layer to a warm layer), and Siete Pecados (a snorkel reef). The water at Kayangan is brackish, calm, and crystal clear. The cliffs around Coron Island are dramatic limestone walls.</p>
<p>El Nido's signature tour is Tour A (Big Lagoon, Small Lagoon, Secret Lagoon, Shimizu Island, Seven Commandos Beach). The lagoons are open saltwater bays surrounded by limestone cliffs and the kayak rentals at Big Lagoon are the headline activity. The water is clear but the depth varies and the snorkel stops are coral-and-reef.</p>
<h2>The Diving</h2>
<p>Coron is the better dive base. The Japanese World War II shipwrecks in Coron Bay are the famous dive sites and the visibility is good year-round. The dive shops are clustered in the town and the prices are competitive. Wreck diving requires an Advanced Open Water cert for most of the deeper sites.</p>
<p>El Nido has reef diving but it is the secondary experience to the boat tours. The diving is closer to a snorkel-plus dive rather than the technical wreck diving in Coron.</p>
<h2>The Cost</h2>
<p>El Nido is the more expensive of the two for accommodation and dining. Coron is the more affordable base with a wider range of mid-range inns. Boat tour rates are roughly comparable (1,200 to 2,000 pesos per person on a shared tour).</p>
<h2>The Crowd</h2>
<p>El Nido is busier across the year. The lagoons at Big Lagoon and Small Lagoon have implemented daily visitor caps and the boats now stagger arrival times, but the islands still feel crowded on peak weekends.</p>
<p>Coron is busy too but the islands are larger and the boats spread out more. Kayangan Lake has a small queue at the entrance climb but the lake itself is wide enough to feel calm.</p>
<h2>The First-Timer Pick</h2>
<p>If this is your first Palawan trip and you have three to four days: pick one, not both. El Nido is the easier pick for the iconic lagoon photos and the long beach base. Coron is the easier pick for the wreck diving and the cheaper food.</p>
<h2>The Combined Pick</h2>
<p>If you have six to seven days, do both. Fly into El Nido (via Lio airport or via Puerto Princesa and a van), spend three days on the boat tours, then take the ferry or the expedition cruise to Coron, spend three more days on the wrecks and Kayangan. This is the sulit Palawan plan for the longer holiday.</p>
<h2>The Honest Read</h2>
<p>El Nido is the visual postcard. Coron is the dive-and-lake one. The choice depends on what you want from the trip, not on which one looks better in a single photo.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Coron or El Nido: Choosing Your Palawan Base | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm honest pick between Coron and El Nido for the first-time Palawan traveler: vibe, boat tours, diving, cost, and crowd compared.',
