    // 14. MAGALAWA ISLAND ZAMBALES OVERNIGHT SLOW PLAN
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://wanderera.com/magalawa-island/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Wander Era',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Magalawa Island, Zambales: A Slow Overnight Plan',
        'slug' => 'magalawa-island-zambales-slow-overnight-plan',
        'excerpt' => 'Magalawa Island is the calm 56-hectare Zambales sandbar with cheap camping and a long quiet beach. Here is the slow overnight read.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Magalawa Island is a 56-hectare island off the coast of Palauig, Zambales, about four to five hours north of Manila by bus. The island is divided into two camps (Armada Resort and Ruiz Resort) and a small fishing village. The famous draw is the long sandbar that stretches off the south side at low tide and the calm clear water on the western beach. The crowds are small and the price is sulit for a calm Zambales overnight.</p>
<p>This is a slow two-day read. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>How to Get There</h2>
<p>From Manila, take a Victory Liner bus from Cubao or Pasay bound for Sta. Cruz, Zambales. The bus passes through Olongapo, Iba, and Masinloc before reaching Palauig. Fare is around 400 to 500 pesos and the trip is five to six hours depending on traffic. Tell the conductor you are going to Magalawa Island and they will drop you at the Brgy. Pangolingan junction in Palauig.</p>
<p>From the junction, take a tricycle to the boat terminal (around 100 pesos for the tricycle and a 15-minute ride). At the boat terminal, the banca crossing to the island is around 30 to 50 pesos per person on a shared boat, or 250 to 350 pesos for a private banca. The crossing takes 10 to 15 minutes.</p>
<h2>The Two Resort Camps</h2>
<p>Armada Resort is on the north side of the island and runs a slightly more developed beach camp with concrete cottages, a small dining area, and rented tents. Ruiz Resort is on the south side and runs a more basic beach camp with native huts and tent camping. Both run small canteens for meals.</p>
<p>Neither camp charges high rates. The day-tour fee is around 100 to 150 pesos and the overnight rates are sulit for the patient traveler. We do not list specific accommodation prices here; ask at the boat terminal for the current rate.</p>
<h2>The Sandbar</h2>
<p>The sandbar is the headline draw. At low tide, a thin tongue of sand extends 200 to 300 meters off the south side of the island, ending in a small shallow pool. The walk along the sandbar at sunset is the iconic Magalawa moment. Check the tide table before you book; the sandbar is fully visible only between half-tide and low tide.</p>
<h2>The Western Beach</h2>
<p>The western beach is the longer of the two main beaches and the one that faces the South China Sea sunset. The sand is fine and the water is calm. Snorkel gear works at the small reef offshore (around 100 meters out). Bring your own gear; the rental sets at the camps are basic.</p>
<h2>The Activities</h2>
<p>Beyond the swim and the sandbar walk, Magalawa is a calm island without organized activities. Some travelers walk the perimeter of the island (around 90 minutes at a slow pace), some kayak along the western beach (kayak rentals at the camps), some ride a banca to the smaller cays just offshore.</p>
<p>The local fishermen offer short boat rides to nearby reefs and fishing stops for a modest fee. Ask at the camp office.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<p>Swim clothes, a quick-dry towel, sunblock (reef-safe if you snorkel), insect repellent, a hat, drinking water (the canteens sell bottled water but the price is double), a power bank (the camp generators run on a fixed schedule), and a flashlight for the night walks. Cash for the camp fees and meals; the island has no ATM.</p>
<h2>The Food</h2>
<p>The camp canteens serve simple Filipino meals: fried fish or grilled tilapia with rice, sinigang na isda, adobo, fried chicken. Breakfast is the standard tapsilog or eggs with rice. Meals are around 150 to 250 pesos. The fresh fish is the order to get; the catch is from the local fishermen earlier the same day.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>March through May is the warm dry window with the calmest sea and the most reliable sandbar visibility. December through February is cooler but the sea is choppier on windy days. June through October is the rainy season; the boats still run but the visits are weather-dependent.</p>
<p>Magalawa is the calm Zambales island for travelers who want a slow overnight without the Anawangin or Capones crowd. Sulit for the patient traveler who can sleep in a tent or a basic native hut.</p>
