    // 15. TAAL HERITAGE TOWN VIGAN OF THE SOUTH WALK
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://wanderera.com/taal-heritage-town-vigan-south/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Wander Era',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Taal Heritage Town Batangas: A Vigan of the South Walk',
        'slug' => 'taal-heritage-town-batangas-vigan-south-walk',
        'excerpt' => 'Taal in Batangas is the ancestral home town with the largest Catholic church in Asia. Here is the calm half-day heritage walk.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Taal is a small heritage town in Batangas, about two and a half hours south of Manila on the SLEX-STAR route. The town has the Basilica of Saint Martin of Tours (the largest Catholic church in Asia by floor area), rows of preserved 19th-century ancestral homes, and small workshops still making barong tagalog and balisong knives the traditional way. The town earned the nickname "Vigan of the South" for the cobblestone-feel of the heritage streets, though the comparison is loose; Taal has fewer streets but more living-house museums than Vigan.</p>
<p>This is a calm half-day walk. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>How to Get There</h2>
<p>From Manila, take a bus from Cubao or Buendia bound for Lemery, Batangas. Fare is around 200 pesos and the trip is two and a half to three hours. From the Lemery terminal, take a jeepney to Taal (15 minutes, 20 pesos). The jeepney drops you at the Taal town plaza.</p>
<p>If you drive, exit SLEX at Santo Tomas, take STAR Tollway to the Lemery exit, then follow the heritage signs to Taal town center.</p>
<h2>The Basilica of Saint Martin of Tours</h2>
<p>Start at the basilica. The current building dates to 1856 (the original from 1572 was destroyed by the Taal Volcano eruption of 1754) and the floor area is 96 by 45 meters, the largest in Asia. The interior is whitewashed and bright, with a high vaulted ceiling and a baroque retablo. Entry is free and the church is open daily; modest dress code applies.</p>
<p>Climb the bell tower if it is open (small donation). The tower view covers the town plaza, the heritage streets, and the Taal Lake in the distance.</p>
<h2>The Heritage Houses</h2>
<p>From the basilica, walk down the cobblestone streets behind the plaza. Three ancestral homes are open as living-house museums:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Casa Apacible</strong>: an 1850s home with original furniture, family portraits, and a small chapel. Admission is around 50 pesos.</li>
<li><strong>Marcela Agoncillo House</strong>: the home of the woman who sewed the first Philippine flag in 1898. Entry is free; the house is run by the National Historical Commission.</li>
<li><strong>Felipe Agoncillo Museum</strong>: the home of the Philippine peace negotiator after the 1898 war. Admission is around 50 pesos and the house has a small library of original documents.</li>
</ul>
<p>Allow 30 to 45 minutes per house. The tours are usually self-guided with a small printed brochure.</p>
<h2>The Barong and Balisong Workshops</h2>
<p>Taal has been famous for hand-embroidered barong tagalog and traditional balisong (butterfly knife) for over a century. Small workshops along Calle M.H. del Pilar still run the traditional way: hand embroidery on pina or jusi cloth for the barong, hand-forging and assembly for the balisong.</p>
<p>Drop in at one of the workshops to watch the embroidery (the slow detail work) and to look at the finished pieces. The barong shops are clustered near the plaza; the balisong workshops are on the road out toward Lemery. Buying a finished barong or a small balisong is the pasalubong move; the workmanship is the highest in the country.</p>
<h2>The Tahong Market</h2>
<p>Taal is on the coast of Balayan Bay and the local market sells fresh tahong (mussels), tawilis (small lake fish from Taal Lake), and the famous Batangas longganisa. Drop in at the public market behind the town plaza for the freshest catch; mornings are best.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat</h2>
<p>For lunch, the small carinderias around the plaza serve Batangueno classics: bulalo, kaldereta, sinigang sa miso, and tapang Taal (the local cured beef). For a more developed dining setting, Cafe de Lipa and Don Juan's BBQ are nearby.</p>
<p>For pasalubong, buy the local Batangas barako coffee, hand-rolled longganisa, and the small kapeng barako biscuits.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry season and the easiest walking weather. The town is calm year-round; the heritage houses do not close for weather. Weekends in February and March (Heritage Month) can be busy with school field trips; weekdays are quieter.</p>
<p>Avoid the town during the rare Taal Volcano alert; the volcano is 20 kilometers across the lake and the ashfall reaches the town when the wind blows north.</p>
<h2>Pair It With</h2>
<p>Pair the morning Taal walk with a Tagaytay afternoon (taal volcano view from across the lake) or with a slow lunch in Lipa (the Batangas capital, 30 minutes inland). The Taal-Tagaytay-Lipa loop fits a full day from Manila.</p>
<p>Taal is the calm heritage walk for travelers who want a slower Vigan-style day closer to Manila. Sulit for the patient traveler.</p>
