    // 16. TULAPOS MARINE SANCTUARY SIQUIJOR SNORKEL MORNING
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://wanderera.com/tulapos-marine-sanctuary-siquijor/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Wander Era',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Tulapos Marine Sanctuary, Siquijor: A Calm Snorkel Morning',
        'slug' => 'tulapos-marine-sanctuary-siquijor-calm-snorkel-morning',
        'excerpt' => 'Tulapos is the quiet Siquijor marine sanctuary on the east coast with mangroves, corals, and a small beach. Here is the calm half-day read.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Tulapos Marine Sanctuary sits on the east coast of Siquijor in the town of Enrique Villanueva, about 30 minutes by scooter from the main port in Larena. The sanctuary covers 14 hectares of beach, mangrove forest, coral reef, and seagrass meadow, and it has been a community-managed protected area since 1986. The site stays calmer than the more famous Cambugahay Falls or Salagdoong Beach, which is part of the reason the snorkeling here is still good.</p>
<p>This is a calm half-day read. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>How to Get There</h2>
<p>From the port in Larena, rent a scooter (around 350 to 400 pesos for a day) and ride east along the coastal road through Enrique Villanueva. The ride is around 30 minutes on a paved road with light traffic. The signage for Tulapos is small but the locals know the turn-off; ask at the small store before the bridge.</p>
<p>If you are based in Siquijor town or San Juan, the ride is longer (45 minutes from Siquijor town, one hour from San Juan). A tricycle from the Larena port runs around 400 to 500 pesos for a day-rental round trip.</p>
<h2>The Entrance and Fee</h2>
<p>The sanctuary office is a small barangay hall at the entrance. Register, pay the small fee (around 50 pesos per person), and rent snorkel gear if needed (basic mask and snorkel for 100 to 150 pesos). The office holds the trail map and the marine sanctuary rules.</p>
<h2>The Mangrove Walk</h2>
<p>The sanctuary has a 200-meter boardwalk through the mangrove forest behind the beach. The walk takes 15 to 20 minutes at a slow pace and the mangrove canopy is dense in the older sections. Look for the small mudskippers in the tidal pools and the small reef fish in the channels.</p>
<p>The boardwalk is shaded and the morning walk is cool even in the dry season.</p>
<h2>The Snorkel Site</h2>
<p>The reef starts about 30 to 40 meters off the beach and runs parallel to the shore for around 200 meters. The corals are mostly hard species (table, finger, and brain corals) and the small reef fish are abundant. Visibility is typically 8 to 15 meters depending on the tide.</p>
<p>The site is shallow (one to three meters at most spots) and suitable for first-time snorkelers. The boundary of the sanctuary is marked by small buoys; stay inside. No fishing, no anchoring, no collecting are the standing rules.</p>
<h2>The Beach</h2>
<p>The beach at the sanctuary is short (around 200 meters) with white sand and a few small huts for shade. The water is calm and the swimming area is sectioned off from the snorkel reef. Bring a packed lunch or order from the small canteen at the office; the canteen has basic Filipino meals (around 150 pesos).</p>
<h2>The Etiquette</h2>
<p>Tulapos is a community-managed sanctuary and the rules are real. Do not touch the corals. Do not feed the fish. Do not collect shells. Do not bring your own snorkel set with fins (the fins are not allowed in the shallow reef sections). The community rangers patrol the area on weekends and they will ask non-compliant visitors to leave.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<p>Swim clothes, a rash guard or a long-sleeve t-shirt (reef-safe sunscreen is recommended but the rash guard is the cleaner option), drinking water, a small dry bag, a packed lunch or cash for the canteen, and a hat for the boardwalk walk. Reef shoes if you have sensitive feet; the shallow reef has some sharp coral edges.</p>
<h2>Pair It With</h2>
<p>Pair the Tulapos morning with a stop at the nearby Salagdoong Beach (15 minutes south), the old Cantabon Cave (45 minutes inland), or a slow lunch at one of the small Enrique Villanueva carinderias. The combined half-day fits a calm Siquijor scooter loop.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>March through May is the dry, warm window with the calmest sea and the clearest snorkel water. December through February is the cooler but still fine window. June through October is the rainy season; the snorkeling is hit-or-miss and the visibility drops.</p>
<p>Tulapos is the calm Siquijor snorkel spot for travelers who want a quieter morning than Salagdoong. Sulit for the patient traveler.</p>
