    [
        'source_url' => 'https://wanderera.com/cambugahay-falls-siquijor/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Wander Era',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Cambugahay Falls, Siquijor: A Calm Rope-Swing Afternoon',
        'slug' => 'cambugahay-falls-siquijor-calm-rope-swing-afternoon',
        'excerpt' => 'Cambugahay is the three-tier waterfall in Lazi, Siquijor with the famous rope swings. Here is the calm afternoon read.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Cambugahay Falls is the famous three-tier waterfall in Lazi, Siquijor, about 45 minutes by scooter from Siquijor town. The falls have a wide cascade, three swimming pools at different levels, and a row of rope swings strung from the trees over the largest pool. The setting is photogenic and the swims are real, which is why the falls are the most visited spot on the island.</p>
<p>This is a calm afternoon read. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>How to Get There</h2>
<p>From Siquijor port, rent a scooter (around 350 to 400 pesos for a day) and ride south along the coastal road through San Juan and Lazi. The ride is around 45 minutes on a paved road. The turn-off to the falls is marked at the Lazi town center; follow the small signs to the parking area.</p>
<p>A tricycle from Siquijor port to the falls runs around 500 to 700 pesos round trip with a wait. A scooter is the cheaper and more flexible option for a full-island day.</p>
<h2>The Entrance</h2>
<p>The entrance fee is around 30 to 50 pesos. From the parking area, a 130-step concrete staircase descends to the falls. The walk down is five to ten minutes; the walk back up is the workout.</p>
<h2>The Three Tiers</h2>
<p>The falls have three main cascades and three swimming pools at different levels:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Top tier</strong>: a smaller cascade with a shallow pool, calmer and quieter. Good for kids and non-swimmers.</li>
<li><strong>Middle tier</strong>: the largest cascade with the wide swimming pool. This is where the rope swings hang from the trees.</li>
<li><strong>Bottom tier</strong>: the deepest pool with a small island in the center. The water flows downstream from here into a small river.</li>
</ul>
<p>The middle tier is the busiest; the top and bottom tiers are usually calmer.</p>
<h2>The Rope Swings</h2>
<p>The rope swings are tied to the trees overhanging the middle pool. There are usually two to three swings active at a time, operated by local kids who charge a small fee (around 20 to 50 pesos per swing). The swing arc carries you 4 to 5 meters out over the pool and drops you in around two meters of water.</p>
<p>The swings are safe for confident swimmers. The local operators check the ropes daily but accidents do happen; do not swing if you cannot swim, and do not let small kids try without an adult swimming alongside.</p>
<h2>The Bamboo Raft</h2>
<p>The local operators offer a short bamboo raft ride that pulls you under the main cascade for a photo. The fee is around 200 pesos per person. The raft is the iconic photo opportunity; the operator takes the photo from the side of the pool.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<p>Swim clothes, a quick-dry towel, a dry bag for valuables (the splash zone is wide and the phone gets wet), reef-safe sunscreen, drinking water, a small snack, and a few small bills for the swings and the bamboo raft. Wear water shoes if you have sensitive feet; the rocks around the pools are smooth but slippery.</p>
<h2>The Crowds and the Timing</h2>
<p>The falls are busiest from 10 a.m. to 2 p.m. when the tour groups from the cruise ships and the resorts arrive. The early morning (7 to 9 a.m.) and the late afternoon (3 to 5 p.m.) are calmer. The light for photos is best in the late morning when the sun is high enough to light the pool through the canopy.</p>
<h2>The Etiquette</h2>
<p>Cambugahay is on Siquijor and the local culture is conservative. The rope swings are casual but loud groups in skimpy swimwear get side eyes from the local families. Dress modestly when you walk between pools; save the bikini for the actual swim.</p>
<p>Carry out everything you bring in. The local barangay maintains the falls on a small budget and the trash from weekend crowds is the main complaint.</p>
<h2>Pair It With</h2>
<p>Pair the falls with a stop at the old Lazi Church (the Lazi Convent is one of the largest in Asia and the church complex is across the road), the Capilay Spring Park in San Juan, and a sunset stop at the Coco Grove or San Juan beach. The combined day fits a calm Siquijor scooter loop.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>March through May is the dry, warm window with the lowest water level (the rope swings are best in this season). June through October is the rainy season; the falls are at their fullest but the water is murky and the swings are sometimes closed for safety.</p>
<p>Cambugahay is the headline Siquijor spot for a reason. Sulit for the patient traveler who arrives early or late and respects the local etiquette.</p>
