    // 18. SUNKEN CEMETERY CAMIGUIN SUNSET CROSSING
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://wanderera.com/white-island-camiguin/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Wander Era',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Sunken Cemetery Camiguin: A Calm Sunset Crossing Read',
        'slug' => 'sunken-cemetery-camiguin-calm-sunset-crossing',
        'excerpt' => 'The Sunken Cemetery off Catarman, Camiguin is the marker cross over a submerged graveyard. Here is the calm sunset boat read.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>The Sunken Cemetery sits in the shallow water off the coast of Catarman, Camiguin, marked by a large white cross visible from the shore. The cemetery was the original Catarman burial ground, submerged when the Mt Vulcan Daan eruption of 1871 lowered the coastal land. The cross was erected in 1982 on the rebuilt seafloor mound and the site has become both a local pilgrimage and a calm sunset stop.</p>
<p>This is a calm read on the sunset crossing. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>How to Get There</h2>
<p>From Mambajao town (the Camiguin capital), ride a tricycle or rent a scooter to Catarman (around 30 minutes on a paved coastal road). The Sunken Cemetery viewing area is along the main road; the parking is on the inland side and the cross is across the road to the seaward side.</p>
<p>From the viewing area, small bancas at the local pier offer short rides out to the cross for a modest fee (around 100 to 150 pesos per person on a shared boat, or 400 to 600 pesos for a private banca). The crossing takes 10 to 15 minutes.</p>
<h2>The Story</h2>
<p>The Catarman parish church (now the Old Catarman Church ruins, a separate site nearby) was destroyed by the eruption of 1871. The cemetery in front of the church was submerged as the coastal land sank. Some of the original gravestones are still visible underwater at low tide; the rest were buried by the volcanic sediment.</p>
<p>The current white cross is the third one on the site. The first two were damaged by typhoons and the current concrete cross dates to 1982. The local government and the Catarman parish maintain the site together.</p>
<h2>The Snorkel</h2>
<p>The water around the cross is shallow (two to four meters at low tide) and the visibility is usually decent. Snorkeling at the site shows some of the original gravestones, the volcanic boulders, and the small reef fish that have colonized the area. The local boat operators provide basic mask and snorkel sets (around 100 pesos).</p>
<p>The site is not a marine sanctuary in the strict sense, but the local government discourages anchoring near the cross and the boat operators use small mooring buoys. Stay near the cross and do not wander off; the current can be tricky on the outer side.</p>
<h2>The Sunset</h2>
<p>The cross faces west and the sunset behind the cross is the iconic photo of Camiguin. The sun drops behind the silhouette of the cross and the surrounding mountain ridges of Misamis Oriental on the mainland. The light is best from 5:30 to 6:15 p.m. depending on the season.</p>
<p>For the sunset boat ride, leave the pier by 5:00 p.m. to be positioned for the photo. Many boat operators run a sunset trip with two or three viewing positions.</p>
<h2>The Old Church Ruins</h2>
<p>Across the road from the viewing area, the ruins of the old Catarman parish church are still standing. The walls are made of coral stone and the original facade survived the eruption. The ruins are a quiet stop and a good companion to the cross. Entry is free.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<p>Swim clothes if you plan to snorkel, a quick-dry towel, a dry bag for valuables, reef-safe sunscreen, drinking water, and a hat. A waterproof phone case or a small action camera for the sunset photos. Cash for the banca and the snorkel rental.</p>
<h2>The Etiquette</h2>
<p>The cemetery is still a place of memory for local families. Do not climb the cross, do not pose with the cross in funny ways, do not bring large groups that crowd the small platform at the base. The site is a quiet stop, not a party spot.</p>
<h2>Pair It With</h2>
<p>Pair the sunset crossing with a morning stop at White Island (the sandbar off Mambajao), an afternoon swim at Katibawasan Falls (inland from Mambajao), and a slow Camiguin dinner. The combined day fits a calm Camiguin loop.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry, calm window with the best water clarity and the most reliable sunset weather. June through October is the rainy season; the boat trips run but the sunset is often blocked by clouds.</p>
<p>The Sunken Cemetery is the calm symbol of Camiguin's volcanic past and the sunset is the moment that frames it. Sulit for the patient traveler.</p>
