    // 19. KATUNGGAN ECO PARK CAMIGUIN MANGROVE WALK
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://wanderera.com/katunggan-park-camiguin/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Wander Era',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Katunggan Eco Park Camiguin: A Calm Mangrove Walk',
        'slug' => 'katunggan-eco-park-camiguin-calm-mangrove-walk',
        'excerpt' => 'Katunggan is the Camiguin community mangrove park with a long bamboo boardwalk. Here is the calm half-day read.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Katunggan Eco Park sits in the town of Mahinog, on the southeast coast of Camiguin, about 45 minutes by scooter or tricycle from Mambajao. The park is a community-run mangrove reserve with a long bamboo boardwalk through the canopy, a small viewing tower, and a quiet shoreline that faces the Bohol Sea. The site is calm, the trail is shaded, and the fee is small.</p>
<p>This is a calm half-day read. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>How to Get There</h2>
<p>From Mambajao, ride a tricycle (around 400 pesos round trip with wait) or rent a scooter (around 300 to 400 pesos for the day) and ride east along the coastal road through Mahinog. The turn-off to Katunggan is marked at the main road; follow the small signs to the park entrance.</p>
<p>The road from Mambajao is paved and the ride is around 45 minutes at a slow pace. The last kilometer to the park is a small barangay road with light traffic.</p>
<h2>The Entrance and Fee</h2>
<p>The entrance fee is around 50 pesos per person. The small park office holds the trail map and the rules. The walk is self-guided but a local guide is available for a modest fee (around 200 pesos for a small group).</p>
<h2>The Bamboo Boardwalk</h2>
<p>The boardwalk is the headline draw. It runs around 600 meters through the mangrove canopy, with sections elevated above the high-tide line and other sections at the water level. The bamboo construction is hand-built by the local community and the maintenance is ongoing; some sections are newer than others.</p>
<p>Walking time at a slow pace is 30 to 45 minutes for the full loop. The canopy is shaded and the air is cool even at midday. The boardwalk is wide enough for two-way traffic and there are small bench rests along the route.</p>
<h2>The Mangrove Ecosystem</h2>
<p>The park has six to eight species of mangrove growing across the site, with the dominant species being the Rhizophora apiculata (bakau) and the Avicennia marina (api-api). The canopy is dense in the older sections and the prop roots create the classic mangrove cathedral effect.</p>
<p>Look for the small mudskippers in the tidal pools, the crabs scuttling in the leaf litter, and the small mangrove kingfishers in the canopy. Birdwatching is best in the early morning (6 to 8 a.m.) and the late afternoon (4 to 6 p.m.).</p>
<h2>The Viewing Tower</h2>
<p>At the midpoint of the boardwalk, a small bamboo tower climbs above the canopy to a viewing platform around six meters above the ground. The view from the tower covers the mangrove canopy, the Bohol Sea, and the small fishing boats anchored offshore. The tower is small (capacity around six to eight at a time); be patient if a group is already up.</p>
<h2>The Shoreline</h2>
<p>The boardwalk ends at a small shoreline section with a sandy beach and a few benches. The beach is not a swimming beach (the seagrass and the small reefs are protected) but it is a calm spot for a quiet break. Bring a packed lunch or order from the small canteen at the office.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<p>Closed walking shoes, drinking water, insect repellent (the mangrove has mosquitoes especially in the late afternoon), a hat, and a small snack. Binoculars if you are a birdwatcher. A small dry bag if you plan to dip your feet at the shoreline. Cash for the entrance fee and the canteen.</p>
<h2>The Etiquette</h2>
<p>Katunggan is a community-managed reserve and the rules are real. Do not pick up shells. Do not feed the wildlife. Do not bring loud music or speakers (the bird population is sensitive). Stay on the boardwalk; do not walk on the mud flats.</p>
<p>Carry out everything. The community manages the park on a small budget and the volunteer rangers maintain the boardwalk weekly.</p>
<h2>Pair It With</h2>
<p>Pair the morning Katunggan walk with a stop at Mantigue Island (a 10-minute banca crossing from Mahinog, with white sand and a small marine sanctuary), an afternoon swim at Ardent Hot Springs (inland from Mambajao), and a Camiguin dinner. The combined day fits a calm island loop.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry, calm window with the easiest walking weather. June through October is the rainy season; the boardwalk is still open but the rain makes the bamboo slippery.</p>
<p>Katunggan is the calm slow alternative to the busier Camiguin tourist circuit. Sulit for the patient traveler.</p>
