    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://wanderera.com/visayas-tourist-spots/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Wander Era',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Hinagdanan Cave Dauis, Panglao: A Calm Swim Stop',
        'slug' => 'hinagdanan-cave-dauis-panglao-calm-swim-stop',
        'excerpt' => 'Hinagdanan is the small Dauis cave with an underground swimming lagoon. Here is the calm half-hour stop read.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Hinagdanan Cave sits in the municipality of Dauis on Panglao Island, about 15 minutes by tricycle from the main beach strip at Alona. The cave is small by Philippine standards (around 100 meters of accessible chamber) but it has a clear underground lagoon, two natural skylights that let the daylight in, and a swim that lasts as long as you want. The visit is calm and short; most travelers spend 30 to 45 minutes from arrival to departure.</p>
<p>This is a calm half-hour stop read. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>How to Get There</h2>
<p>From Alona Beach or Doljo Beach, ride a tricycle to Dauis. Fare is around 100 to 150 pesos and the ride is 15 to 20 minutes. The cave is in a residential area; the small entrance is at the end of a narrow road and the signage is modest.</p>
<p>If you are based in Tagbilaran City, the cave is 30 minutes south by tricycle or jeepney. The Panglao Bridge crossing is the main route.</p>
<h2>The Entrance and Fee</h2>
<p>The entrance fee is around 50 pesos for the cave walk only, and around 75 pesos if you plan to swim in the lagoon. The fee includes the use of the small changing room and the dressing area. The cave is open from 8 a.m. to 5 p.m.</p>
<p>The cave is privately owned by a local family who built the original concrete stairs down into the chamber. The family also operates a small canteen at the entrance.</p>
<h2>The Descent</h2>
<p>The entrance to the cave is a narrow stairway that descends around 12 to 15 meters into the chamber. The stairway has handrails and good lighting. The descent takes one to two minutes; the climb back up is the small workout.</p>
<p>The main chamber opens up into a wide space with stalactites and stalagmites along the walls. The natural skylights are at the ceiling and the light pours into the chamber in two visible cones.</p>
<h2>The Lagoon</h2>
<p>The underground lagoon is the centerpiece of the cave. The water is brackish (slightly salty due to a connection to the sea) and clear. The depth varies from one meter at the edge to around three to four meters at the center. The water is cool year-round and the lighting from the skylights gives the lagoon a soft blue-green glow.</p>
<p>Swimming is allowed but the cave management has a maximum capacity (around 10 to 15 people at a time). On busy weekends a small queue forms at the stairway; weekdays are calmer.</p>
<h2>The Photo</h2>
<p>The iconic Hinagdanan photo is taken from the swimming platform looking toward one of the skylights, with the light cone illuminating a swimmer in the lagoon. The light is best between 10 a.m. and 2 p.m. when the sun is high enough to enter the skylight directly.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<p>Swim clothes, a quick-dry towel, a dry bag for valuables, a small snack, and drinking water. Closed shoes with a grippy sole (the cave floor is wet and slippery in some sections). A waterproof phone case for the lagoon photos.</p>
<h2>The Etiquette</h2>
<p>The cave is a small protected space and the rules are real. Do not touch the stalactites or the cave formations. Do not bring food into the cave (eat at the canteen above). Do not use flash photography that disturbs the bats in the upper chambers. Do not bring loud groups; the chamber echoes and the noise is sharp.</p>
<h2>Pair It With</h2>
<p>Pair the cave with a morning at the Panglao Bee Farm (10 minutes from Hinagdanan), a quick stop at the Dauis Church (a 15-minute drive, with a famous well inside the chancel), and an afternoon swim at Alona Beach. The combined day fits a calm Panglao loop.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry season with the most reliable visibility through the skylights. June through October is the rainy season; the cave is open but the natural lighting is dimmer.</p>
<p>Hinagdanan is the short calm side-trip in a Bohol day. Sulit for the patient traveler who plans a half-day around it.</p>
