    // 21. MANJUYOD SANDBAR NEGROS ORIENTAL DAWN RIDE
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://wanderera.com/visayas-tourist-spots/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Wander Era',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Manjuyod Sandbar, Negros Oriental: A Calm Dawn Ride',
        'slug' => 'manjuyod-sandbar-negros-oriental-calm-dawn-ride',
        'excerpt' => 'Manjuyod is the seven-kilometer white sandbar off Bais Bay that appears at low tide. Here is the calm dawn boat read.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Manjuyod Sandbar sits off the coast of Bais Bay in Negros Oriental, about two hours by van from Dumaguete. The sandbar is a seven-kilometer ribbon of white sand that emerges from the sea at low tide and disappears under shallow water at high tide. The locals call it the "Maldives of the Philippines," and while the comparison is loose, the optics on a calm sunny morning are real.</p>
<p>This is a calm dawn read. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>How to Get There</h2>
<p>From Dumaguete, take a bus or van to Bais City (around 1.5 to 2 hours, fare around 120 pesos). From the Bais terminal, take a tricycle to the Capinahan Wharf (around 100 pesos, 15-minute ride). The wharf is the launching point for the sandbar boats.</p>
<p>Most travelers book a day tour through a Dumaguete operator. The package includes the van transfer, the banca rental, the sandbar landing, and lunch on a stilt cottage. Independent travelers can negotiate at the wharf for around 3,000 to 5,000 pesos per banca (capacity 10 to 15).</p>
<h2>The Tide Window</h2>
<p>The sandbar is visible only at low tide. Check the tide table for Bais before booking; the sandbar emerges at around half-tide and is fully exposed at low tide. The window between half-tide-down and half-tide-up is around four to five hours.</p>
<p>The best days are the new moon and the full moon dates when the tide range is widest. Mid-tide days have a shorter sandbar window. The local boatmen know the tide cycle by heart; ask them for the best day to book.</p>
<h2>The Dawn Departure</h2>
<p>For the calmest sea and the cleanest light, leave the wharf at first light (around 5:30 a.m.). The banca ride to the sandbar takes 30 to 45 minutes. Arriving at the sandbar by 6:30 a.m. gives you the sunrise on the open water and the first low-tide window of the morning.</p>
<p>The afternoon departures (around 1 p.m. for the second low-tide window) are warmer but the light is harder. Pick the morning for the calmer experience.</p>
<h2>The Sandbar Walk</h2>
<p>At low tide, the sandbar is wide enough to walk along the center for several kilometers. The sand is fine and white and the surrounding water is shallow enough to wade in. The water clarity is excellent on a calm day.</p>
<p>The famous photo is the long walk along the sandbar with the open sea on both sides. Frame the shot with the sandbar curving toward the horizon and the small banca anchored in the distance.</p>
<h2>The Stilt Cottages</h2>
<p>A row of small stilt cottages is anchored in the shallow water off the sandbar. The cottages are operated by the local cooperatives and the day-tour packages usually include lunch served on the cottage deck. The cottage rental is around 1,500 to 3,000 pesos depending on the size and the operator.</p>
<p>Lunch is the standard local Filipino menu: grilled fish, kinilaw, fresh seaweed salad, rice, and a fruit dessert. The food is fresh and the setting is one of the calmest dining spots in Negros.</p>
<h2>The Dolphin Watching</h2>
<p>Bais Bay is also one of the best dolphin watching areas in the Visayas. The local pods of spinner dolphins and Fraser's dolphins are commonly sighted at dawn. Most banca operators include a 30 to 45-minute dolphin search as part of the package.</p>
<p>The sightings are not guaranteed but the chances are high in the morning window (5:30 to 8:30 a.m.). Bring a camera with a zoom; the dolphins surface 20 to 50 meters from the banca.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<p>Swim clothes, a quick-dry towel, reef-safe sunscreen, a hat, sunglasses, a dry bag for valuables, drinking water, and a small snack. The sandbar has no shade beyond the cottage; bring a light cover-up for the longer stops. Cash for the boat fees, the lunch, and the small tips.</p>
<h2>The Etiquette</h2>
<p>The sandbar is a fragile natural feature. Do not bury trash in the sand. Do not collect shells. Do not leave anything behind. The local cooperatives manage the site and the cleanliness depends on visitor cooperation.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>March through May is the dry, warm window with the calmest sea and the most reliable sandbar visibility. December through February is cooler but the wind can pick up. June through October is the rainy season; the boats run on calm days but the sandbar visits are weather-dependent.</p>
<p>Manjuyod is the calm postcard moment of Negros Oriental. Sulit for the patient traveler who books the dawn departure on a low-tide morning.</p>
