    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 22. BOHOL TO SIQUIJOR FERRY HONEST SCHEDULE GUIDE
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://wanderera.com/bohol-to-siquijor-ferry/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Wander Era',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Bohol to Siquijor Ferry: An Honest Schedule Guide',
        'slug' => 'bohol-to-siquijor-ferry-honest-schedule-guide',
        'excerpt' => 'Bohol to Siquijor by ferry runs via Tagbilaran or via Dumaguete. Here is the honest read on the routes, schedules, and fares.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Bohol to Siquijor by ferry is a common Visayas hop, but the route is not a single direct line. The standard options run via Tagbilaran (Bohol) with a stopover or transfer in Dumaguete (Negros Oriental). A few seasonal direct ferries run on limited schedules. This guide covers the realistic options for the patient traveler.</p>
<p>Tara, here is the kwento.</p>
<h2>Option One: Tagbilaran to Dumaguete to Siquijor</h2>
<p>This is the most reliable route year-round. From the Tagbilaran port, board an OceanJet or Lite Shipping fastcraft bound for Dumaguete. Trip time is around two hours and the fare is around 600 to 900 pesos. Daily departures run from early morning to late afternoon.</p>
<p>Arrive in Dumaguete, walk or ride a short tricycle to the adjacent ferry terminal, and board an OceanJet, Aleson Shipping, or Maayo Shipping ferry to Siquijor. Trip time is around 45 minutes to one hour and the fare is around 200 to 400 pesos. Multiple daily departures.</p>
<p>The total travel time from Tagbilaran to Siquijor (including the Dumaguete transfer) is around four to five hours.</p>
<h2>Option Two: Tagbilaran Direct (Seasonal)</h2>
<p>OceanJet occasionally runs a direct Tagbilaran to Siquijor route, but the schedule changes by season. Check the OceanJet website or call the Tagbilaran port for the current direct schedule. When the direct runs, trip time is around two hours and the fare is around 800 to 1,200 pesos.</p>
<p>The direct route is convenient but not guaranteed. Build the transfer route into your plan and treat the direct as a bonus if it is running.</p>
<h2>Option Three: Cebu to Tagbilaran to Dumaguete to Siquijor</h2>
<p>If you are starting in Cebu, the standard route is Cebu to Tagbilaran (by OceanJet or 2GO fastcraft, around two hours, 800 to 1,500 pesos), then Tagbilaran to Dumaguete (option one above), then Dumaguete to Siquijor. Total travel time is around eight to nine hours; do this as a slow full-day plan.</p>
<h2>The Tickets</h2>
<p>All major operators allow online booking (OceanJet, Lite Shipping, 2GO, Aleson). Book the Tagbilaran to Dumaguete leg in advance during peak season (December, April, May, October) to lock in your preferred schedule. The Dumaguete to Siquijor leg is usually walk-in friendly; the ferries run frequently.</p>
<p>Bring a printed or screenshot copy of your booking confirmation. The port staff at Tagbilaran and Dumaguete accept both physical tickets and digital QR codes.</p>
<h2>The Port Experience</h2>
<p>The Tagbilaran port is small but organized. Check-in opens 30 minutes before departure; the security check is at the entrance and the boarding gate is at the pier. Bring a valid government ID; the port requires identity verification before boarding.</p>
<p>The Dumaguete port is busier but the layout is similar. The Siquijor-bound ferries dock at the adjacent terminal; the walk between the two is around 200 meters.</p>
<p>The Siquijor port at Larena (or Siquijor town, depending on the operator) is small and the tricycle stand is at the gate.</p>
<h2>What to Pack</h2>
<p>A light sweater (the fastcraft cabins are air-conditioned to a chill), a snack, drinking water (one bottle per leg), a power bank, and motion sickness pills if you are prone (the ferries run through the Cebu Strait which can be choppy in the dry season).</p>
<h2>The Sea Conditions</h2>
<p>December to May is the calm dry-season window. June to October is the rainy season; the ferries still run but the sea can be choppy on the afternoon legs. The morning departures are usually calmer than the afternoon ones.</p>
<p>Avoid Holy Week, Christmas week, and Labor Day weekend if you can; the ferries are fully booked and the ports are packed. Book at least two weeks ahead for these dates.</p>
<h2>The Tip</h2>
<p>If you have time, treat the ferry day as a slow travel day. Arrive in Dumaguete on the Tagbilaran ferry by mid-morning, have a slow lunch at the Boulevard (the famous Dumaguete waterfront), and catch a late-afternoon ferry to Siquijor for the sunset arrival. The pacing is gentler and you get a free Dumaguete half-day.</p>
<p>Bohol to Siquijor is a multi-leg trip but the route is well-trodden and the operators are reliable. Sulit for the patient traveler who builds in the buffer time.</p>
