        'title' => 'Cebu to Siquijor Ferry: An Honest Schedule Guide',
        'slug' => 'cebu-to-siquijor-ferry-honest-schedule-guide',
        'excerpt' => 'Cebu to Siquijor by ferry is a multi-leg hop or an overnight direct trip. Here is the honest read on the routes and fares.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Cebu to Siquijor by ferry is one of the longer Visayas hops, with three main route options: the transfer route via Bohol or Negros, the direct overnight route, or the indirect overnight via Larena. The best pick depends on your departure time, your budget, and your patience for transfers. This guide covers the realistic options.</p>
<p>Tara, here is the kwento.</p>
<h2>Option One: Cebu to Dumaguete (Direct), then Dumaguete to Siquijor</h2>
<p>The cleanest day-trip route. From Cebu City, board a Cokaliong Shipping overnight ferry to Dumaguete. The departure is usually 7 to 9 p.m. and the arrival in Dumaguete is around 5 to 6 a.m. Fare is around 700 to 1,400 pesos depending on cabin class. The overnight cabin saves you a hotel night.</p>
<p>Arrive in Dumaguete at dawn, walk to the adjacent ferry terminal, and catch the 8 a.m. or 9 a.m. OceanJet or Maayo to Siquijor. Trip time is 45 minutes to one hour and the fare is around 200 to 400 pesos. Total travel time from Cebu to Siquijor is around 11 to 13 hours, mostly slept through.</p>
<h2>Option Two: Cebu to Tagbilaran, then Tagbilaran to Dumaguete to Siquijor</h2>
<p>This is the multi-leg day route. From Cebu City, board an OceanJet fastcraft to Tagbilaran (around two hours, 800 to 1,500 pesos). Transfer at Tagbilaran to the Dumaguete-bound fastcraft (around two hours, 600 to 900 pesos). Transfer in Dumaguete to the Siquijor-bound ferry (around 45 minutes to one hour).</p>
<p>Total travel time is around eight to nine hours of riding plus the transfer waits. Plan for a full slow day; do not book a same-day evening dinner in Siquijor.</p>
<h2>Option Three: Cebu Direct to Larena (Seasonal)</h2>
<p>Cokaliong Shipping occasionally runs a direct Cebu to Larena overnight ferry. The departure is around 7 p.m. and the arrival in Larena is around 7 a.m. the next day. Fare is around 800 to 1,500 pesos depending on cabin class. Check the Cokaliong website or call the Cebu port for the current schedule; the direct route is not always active.</p>
<p>The direct overnight is the calmest of the three options. You sleep through the trip and you arrive on Siquijor without transfers. Book at least two weeks ahead during the high season.</p>
<h2>The Tickets</h2>
<p>All major operators (Cokaliong, OceanJet, Lite Shipping, Maayo) allow online booking. The overnight ferries fill up faster than the day fastcrafts; book early during peak season. The Dumaguete to Siquijor leg is usually walk-in friendly.</p>
<p>Bring a printed booking confirmation or a screenshot. The Cebu port accepts both.</p>
<h2>The Port Experience</h2>
<p>The Cebu City port (Pier 1 for OceanJet, Pier 6 for Cokaliong) is large and busy. Arrive 60 to 90 minutes before departure for the security check, the terminal fee, and the boarding. The terminal fee is around 30 to 50 pesos and the porter fee for large bags is around 50 to 100 pesos.</p>
<p>The cabin overnight on Cokaliong is in tourist class or first-class cabins; the bunks are basic but the rooms have air-conditioning, lockers, and a shared bathroom. Bring a light blanket; the air-conditioning is set cold.</p>
<h2>What to Pack</h2>
<p>A light sweater for the cabin air-conditioning, a sleep mask for the cabin, a snack and drinking water (the canteen on board is basic), a power bank, a small toiletry kit, motion sickness pills if needed. Pack a separate small day bag with your essentials; leave the larger luggage in your reserved space.</p>
<h2>The Sea Conditions</h2>
<p>December to May is the calm window with the smoothest overnight rides. June to October is the rainy season; the overnight ferries usually run but the cabin nights can be rough on the open Bohol Sea. Check the weather forecast and the typhoon advisory before sailing.</p>
<h2>The Tip</h2>
<p>If you have the budget, the overnight cabin on Cokaliong is the calmest way to do this trip. You save a hotel night, you arrive rested, and the long sea travel feels like a quick night. The day-trip transfer route is cheaper but tiring.</p>
<p>Cebu to Siquijor is a long but well-served route. Sulit for the patient traveler who picks the overnight option.</p>
