        'excerpt' => 'Dumaguete to Siquijor is the 45-minute fastcraft hop with multiple daily departures. Here is the calm honest read.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Dumaguete to Siquijor by ferry is the shortest Visayas crossing and the easiest leg of the wider Negros-Bohol-Siquijor circuit. The Tanon Strait between the two islands is around 25 kilometers wide and the fastcraft makes the crossing in 45 minutes to one hour. Multiple operators run daily departures from morning to evening.</p>
<p>This is the calm honest read. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>The Operators</h2>
<p>Three main operators run the Dumaguete to Siquijor route:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>OceanJet</strong>: the busiest operator with the most frequent schedule (six to eight daily departures). Fastcraft with air-conditioned cabins.</li>
<li><strong>Maayo Shipping</strong>: a newer fastcraft service with similar frequency. The boats are newer and the cabins are clean.</li>
<li><strong>Aleson Shipping</strong>: the cheaper RORO option for travelers with vehicles. Slower (around 1.5 hours) but cheaper.</li>
</ul>
<p>For most travelers without a vehicle, OceanJet or Maayo is the right pick.</p>
<h2>The Schedule</h2>
<p>OceanJet runs departures roughly every two hours from 6 a.m. to 5 p.m. Maayo runs a similar schedule. The actual times shift seasonally; check the operator websites or call the Dumaguete port for the current schedule.</p>
<p>Aleson runs around two RORO departures per day; the schedule is less frequent but the vehicle slots are available.</p>
<h2>The Fare</h2>
<p>OceanJet and Maayo fastcraft fares are around 200 to 400 pesos for an adult one-way. Aleson RORO fares are around 100 to 200 pesos for an adult passenger; the vehicle fare is separate (around 1,500 to 2,500 pesos depending on size). Children's fares and senior discounts apply.</p>
<p>The terminal fee at Dumaguete is around 30 pesos. The terminal fee at Siquijor (Larena or Siquijor town) is around 30 pesos.</p>
<h2>The Tickets</h2>
<p>Online booking is available on the OceanJet and Maayo websites. Walk-in tickets are usually available at the Dumaguete port counters; the queues are short except on peak weekends. For the popular morning departures (8 a.m., 10 a.m.) during the December and April peak, book one or two days ahead.</p>
<p>Bring a valid government ID. The port requires identity verification before boarding.</p>
<h2>The Port Experience</h2>
<p>The Dumaguete port is on the city waterfront, a 10-minute tricycle ride from the city center. The fastcraft terminal is at the front; the RORO terminal is at the back. Check-in opens 30 minutes before departure and the boarding gate is at the pier.</p>
<p>The Siquijor port is small and the tricycle stand is at the gate. OceanJet and Maayo dock at the Siquijor town port; Aleson docks at the Larena port (around 30 minutes north of Siquijor town by tricycle).</p>
<p>If you want to base in San Juan (the famous beach area), arrive at the Siquijor town port for the shorter tricycle ride. If you want to start at the northern beaches or the Salagdoong area, the Larena port is closer.</p>
<h2>The Crossing</h2>
<p>The 45-minute to one-hour crossing is usually smooth. The Tanon Strait is sheltered between the two islands and the sea is calm on most days. The fastcraft cabin is air-conditioned and basic; there is no food service on board for the short crossing.</p>
<p>Bring a light sweater for the cabin air-conditioning. The seats are basic but comfortable for the short trip.</p>
<h2>What to Pack</h2>
<p>A small bag with your essentials (the main luggage goes in the cargo hold). A light sweater. A snack and a small bottle of water. Motion sickness pills if you are prone, though the Tanon crossing is rarely rough. Cash for the tricycle from the Siquijor port to your accommodation.</p>
<h2>The Sea Conditions</h2>
<p>December to May is the calmest window. June to October is the rainy season; the ferries still run but the afternoon departures can be choppier. The morning departures are usually the calmest.</p>
<p>Avoid the long weekends (Holy Week, Labor Day, All Saints) for walk-in tickets; the boats are fully booked and the port is packed.</p>
<h2>The Tip</h2>
<p>If you are coming from Cebu on the overnight Cokaliong, the 8 a.m. or 10 a.m. OceanJet from Dumaguete is the natural transfer. You arrive in Siquijor by mid-morning with the rest of the day open.</p>
<p>Dumaguete to Siquijor is the easy short crossing. Sulit for the patient traveler who books the morning fastcraft.</p>
