        'excerpt' => 'PITX is the Paranaque Integrated Terminal Exchange for buses to Cavite, Batangas, and southern Luzon. Here is the calm first-timer read.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>The Paranaque Integrated Terminal Exchange (PITX) is the modern multi-operator bus terminal at the corner of Coastal Road and Kennon Road in Paranaque City. It opened in 2018 to consolidate the southern Luzon bus departures that used to be scattered across multiple operator-owned terminals along EDSA. PITX now serves over 100 routes including Cavite, Batangas, Quezon, Bicol, and selected Visayas through 2GO ferry connections.</p>
<p>This is a calm first-timer read. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>How to Get to PITX</h2>
<p>From Makati or BGC, take the EDSA Carousel busway to its southern end at PITX (around 30 to 45 minutes during off-peak hours). The Carousel is the cheapest option (around 25 pesos).</p>
<p>From the airport (NAIA Terminal 1, 2, or 3), the UBE Express airport shuttle runs directly to PITX (around 30 to 45 minutes, fare around 150 pesos). This is the cleanest option for arriving travelers connecting to a province bus.</p>
<p>From Metro Manila by jeepney or modern jeep, multiple routes terminate at PITX. From Pasay LRT (Line 1), a short jeep or UV Express ride brings you to the terminal. Taxi or Grab from anywhere in Metro Manila works; the fare from Makati is around 250 to 400 pesos plus tolls.</p>
<h2>The Layout</h2>
<p>The terminal has three floors and a clear signage system. The ground floor has the public utility vehicle (PUV) stop, the porter station, and the arrival lobby. The first floor has the departure halls organized by destination zone. The second floor has the food court, the convenience stores, and the rest area.</p>
<p>Buses depart from numbered gates on the ground floor. The departure gate is indicated on your ticket and on the departure board.</p>
<h2>The Operators</h2>
<p>The major operators serving PITX include:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>DLTBCo</strong>: routes to Quezon (Lucena, Sariaya, Lucban), Bicol (Naga, Legazpi), and Batangas.</li>
<li><strong>Jam Liner</strong>: routes to Batangas (Lemery, Calatagan, Lipa).</li>
<li><strong>JAC Liner</strong>: routes to Batangas (Lipa, Batangas City, Anilao).</li>
<li><strong>Genesis</strong>: routes to Bataan, Zambales, and Pampanga.</li>
<li><strong>Erjohn and Almark</strong>: routes to Cavite (Tagaytay, Indang, Mendez).</li>
<li><strong>UV Express vans</strong>: routes to Cavite, Laguna, Batangas towns not served by big buses.</li>
</ul>
<p>The terminal also has a 2GO booking counter for the ferry-and-bus combined fares to Visayas destinations.</p>
<h2>The Tickets</h2>
<p>Most operators sell tickets at their counters on the first floor. A few (Genesis, Jam Liner) allow online booking. Walk-in tickets are usually available except on peak weekends and holidays.</p>
<p>Pay in cash or with GCash QR (most counters accept). Keep your ticket; the boarding gate staff scans the QR or stamps the ticket.</p>
<h2>The Boarding</h2>
<p>Boarding opens 30 minutes before departure. The boarding gate is on the ground floor; the gate number is on your ticket. The bus pulls up to the gate, you scan or show your ticket, you board.</p>
<p>Luggage handling is at the gate. The porter loads your bag into the bus cargo hold; tip 20 to 50 pesos for the service if you choose.</p>
<h2>The Amenities</h2>
<p>PITX has a food court with Jollibee, McDonald's, Mang Inasal, KFC, and several Filipino fast-food chains. The 7-Eleven and Mini Stop convenience stores are on the first floor. The rest area on the second floor has phone charging stations and a small nursing room.</p>
<p>The clean public restrooms are on every floor. The PWD facilities are well-marked. The wifi is free but slow; bring your own data.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<p>Your government ID (some operators require it), the booking confirmation if you booked online, cash for the meal stops, a light jacket for the bus air-conditioning (set cold on most routes), a power bank, and motion sickness pills if you are prone.</p>
<h2>The Tip</h2>
<p>Arrive at PITX 45 to 60 minutes before your scheduled departure. Use the first 15 minutes to claim your ticket or scan your booking, the next 15 to grab a meal at the food court, and the last 15 to settle at the boarding gate. The terminal is large and the first time can be disorienting; the buffer time helps.</p>
<p>PITX is the modern bus terminal that consolidated the southern Luzon scatter. Sulit for the patient traveler who arrives early.</p>
