        'title' => 'Solid North P2P Bus Manila to Baguio: A Calm Read',
        'slug' => 'solid-north-p2p-bus-manila-baguio-calm-read',
        'excerpt' => 'Solid North runs P2P deluxe buses from Manila to Baguio in five to six hours. Here is the calm read on the schedule and the ride.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Solid North Transit runs Point-to-Point (P2P) deluxe buses from Manila to Baguio with no stops between terminals. The route uses the NLEX-SCTEX-TPLEX expressway corridor and the trip time is five to six hours depending on traffic. The buses are newer than the standard Victory Liner regular service, with reclining seats, two-by-one configuration, and onboard wifi on most units.</p>
<p>This is the calm read for the patient traveler. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>The Route</h2>
<p>The P2P route runs from the Cubao terminal (Solid North office along EDSA) to the Baguio terminal (Genesis-Joybus compound near SM Baguio). The bus stays on the expressway from the entrance ramp at Balintawak through NLEX, SCTEX (the bypass through Clark), and TPLEX (the Tarlac-Pangasinan-La Union Expressway).</p>
<p>The expressway exit at Rosario, La Union connects to the Marcos Highway up the Cordillera. The climb from Rosario to Baguio is the last 50 kilometers and takes around 1.5 hours.</p>
<h2>The Schedule</h2>
<p>Solid North runs four to six daily P2P departures from Cubao to Baguio, starting at around 4 a.m. and ending at around 11 p.m. The exact departures shift seasonally; check the Solid North website or the Cubao terminal for the current schedule.</p>
<p>Return trips from Baguio to Cubao follow a similar schedule. The last return is usually 11 p.m.</p>
<h2>The Fare</h2>
<p>The P2P fare is higher than the regular Victory Liner ordinary fare but lower than a private van rental. Expect to pay around 750 to 900 pesos one-way depending on the seat class. The deluxe seats are wider with a longer recline; the executive class on some units has a power outlet at every seat.</p>
<p>Children's fares apply for under-12. Senior and PWD discounts apply with valid ID.</p>
<h2>The Tickets</h2>
<p>Online booking is available on the Solid North website and through several aggregator apps (Pinoy Travel, etc.). Walk-in tickets are usually available except on peak weekends (Holy Week, long weekends, Christmas week, summer break).</p>
<p>Book at least one to two days ahead for the morning departures (4 a.m. to 7 a.m.) which fill up fastest. The 4 a.m. departure is the most popular because it arrives in Baguio by 10 a.m. with a full day still ahead.</p>
<h2>The Terminal Experience</h2>
<p>The Cubao terminal is a small office along EDSA. The waiting area has clean seats, restrooms, and a small canteen. Check-in opens 30 minutes before departure. The boarding bay is at the side of the terminal; the bus pulls up and the porter loads the luggage.</p>
<p>The Baguio terminal is the Genesis-Joybus compound near SM Baguio. The compound is on Governor Pack Road, walking distance to the Burnham Park area and a short tricycle ride to the Session Road shops.</p>
<h2>The Onboard Experience</h2>
<p>The Solid North P2P buses are newer than the standard fleet. The seats are reclining with a leg rest, two-by-one configuration in most units. The aisle is wide and the legroom is generous. The air-conditioning is set cold; bring a light sweater.</p>
<p>Onboard wifi is available on most units; the signal is good in the lowland sections and patchy in the Cordillera climb. The unit has a single toilet at the back (clean but small).</p>
<p>There is no scheduled meal stop on the P2P. The bus does a short comfort stop at the SCTEX or TPLEX rest area around the halfway point (around 2.5 hours in). Use the stop for the restroom and a quick snack from the rest-stop vendors.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<p>A light sweater, a small pillow if you can sleep on transit, a snack (no meal service on board), a one-liter water bottle, a power bank, a downloaded podcast or playlist, motion sickness pills if you are prone (the Marcos Highway climb is winding).</p>
<h2>The Tip</h2>
<p>For the 4 a.m. departure, sleep in a Cubao or Quezon City accommodation the night before; the early ride is not the time to be commuting across Manila at 3 a.m. The same logic applies to the 11 p.m. return; book a Baguio accommodation that you can check out of late, or plan an early-evening dinner.</p>
<p>Solid North P2P is the calm comfortable way from Manila to Baguio. Sulit for the patient traveler who books the right departure window.</p>
