    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 28. CAVITE TO BAGUIO COMMUTE WITHOUT A CAR
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://wanderera.com/cavite-to-baguio/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Wander Era',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Cavite to Baguio Commute Without a Car: A Calm Read',
        'slug' => 'cavite-to-baguio-commute-without-car-calm-read',
        'excerpt' => 'Cavite to Baguio without a car needs two transfers via PITX or Cubao. Here is the calm honest read for the patient commuter.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Cavite to Baguio is a 280-kilometer trip that crosses the full length of Metro Manila and then climbs the Cordillera. There is no direct bus from Cavite to Baguio; you transfer at either PITX in Paranaque or one of the Cubao terminals. The total travel time without a car is seven to nine hours depending on the transfer wait and the Manila traffic at the time of crossing.</p>
<p>This is the calm honest read. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>The Two Transfer Options</h2>
<p>There are two reasonable ways to commute from Cavite to Baguio:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Option A: PITX transfer</strong>. Take a Cavite bus or UV Express to PITX in Paranaque, then transfer to a northbound bus (Victory Liner, Genesis, Solid North) to Baguio.</li>
<li><strong>Option B: Cubao transfer</strong>. Take a Cavite bus or UV Express to the Cubao terminal, then transfer to a northbound bus from the Cubao Aurora terminals.</li>
</ul>
<p>PITX is the cleaner transfer with covered walkways and a central booking hall. Cubao is the older transfer with more operators and slightly cheaper fares.</p>
<h2>The PITX Route (Option A)</h2>
<p>From most Cavite towns (Imus, Bacoor, Dasmarinas, Tagaytay, Silang), buses and UV Express vans run to PITX directly. Fare is around 80 to 150 pesos and the trip is 30 to 60 minutes depending on traffic.</p>
<p>At PITX, walk to the northbound departure hall on the first floor and book a Baguio bus. Victory Liner, Genesis-Joybus, and Solid North all have counters here. Departure frequency is around one bus per hour.</p>
<p>Total travel time on this option: 30 to 60 minutes (Cavite to PITX) + 30 to 60 minutes (PITX transfer wait) + 5 to 6 hours (PITX to Baguio) = 6.5 to 8 hours.</p>
<h2>The Cubao Route (Option B)</h2>
<p>From most Cavite towns, buses and UV Express vans run to Pasay or Cubao. Fare is around 80 to 150 pesos and the trip is one to 1.5 hours depending on traffic.</p>
<p>At Cubao, walk to the Victory Liner Aurora terminal or the Genesis terminal nearby. Departure frequency to Baguio is high (one bus every 30 to 60 minutes).</p>
<p>Total travel time on this option: 1 to 1.5 hours (Cavite to Cubao) + 30 to 60 minutes (Cubao transfer wait) + 5 to 6 hours (Cubao to Baguio) = 6.5 to 8.5 hours.</p>
<h2>The Best Departure Window</h2>
<p>The cleanest way to do this trip is to leave Cavite by 4 a.m. or 5 a.m. The Manila traffic is light at this hour, you arrive at PITX or Cubao by 5 a.m. or 6 a.m., and you catch the 6 a.m. or 7 a.m. Baguio bus. Arrival in Baguio is around noon to 1 p.m.</p>
<p>The other clean window is the late night (11 p.m. or midnight departure from Cavite, arriving Manila by 12 a.m. or 1 a.m., catching the 1 a.m. or 2 a.m. Baguio bus, arriving Baguio by 7 a.m. or 8 a.m.). The overnight option saves a hotel night.</p>
<h2>The Tagaytay Variant</h2>
<p>If you are based in Tagaytay or Mendez, the cleanest route is to take a DLTB or Erjohn bus to PITX, then transfer. The Tagaytay buses run frequently and the PITX is the natural transfer.</p>
<p>If you have time, an overnight stop in Tagaytay before the Baguio leg is a calmer plan. Sleep in Tagaytay, catch the early morning bus to PITX, then the 6 a.m. bus to Baguio. The pacing is gentler.</p>
<h2>The Fare</h2>
<p>Total Cavite to Baguio fare is around 600 to 900 pesos for ordinary buses, or around 900 to 1,300 pesos for deluxe and Joybus executive. The PITX terminal fee is around 30 pesos.</p>
<h2>What to Pack</h2>
<p>A small overnight bag (the main luggage goes in the cargo hold), a light sweater, a snack pack, drinking water, a power bank, motion sickness pills if you are prone, a downloaded podcast, and cash for the multiple stages.</p>
<h2>The Tip</h2>
<p>Book the Baguio leg online the day before. The morning departures from PITX and Cubao fill up fast on weekends. The Cavite-Manila leg you can walk in; buses run every 15 to 30 minutes.</p>
<p>Cavite to Baguio without a car is a long but manageable trip. Sulit for the patient commuter who picks the right transfer window.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Cavite to Baguio Without a Car: Calm Read | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm honest read on commuting from Cavite to Baguio without a car, with the PITX and Cubao transfer routes, schedules, and timing tips.',
        'tags' => 'Cavite to Baguio, Bus, Commute, PITX, Travel Guide',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'bacoor',
