    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 29. PANGASINAN BEACH CAMPSITES SLOW ROUNDUP
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://wanderera.com/pangasinan-beach-campsites/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Wander Era',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Pangasinan Beach Campsites: A Calm Slow Roundup',
        'slug' => 'pangasinan-beach-campsites-calm-slow-roundup',
        'excerpt' => 'Pangasinan has eight calm beach campsites from Bolinao to Anda. Here is the slow roundup with what to expect at each.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Pangasinan is one of the underrated beach-camping provinces in northwest Luzon. The coastline stretches from Bolinao on the western tip to Anda on the northern reach, with a string of small barangay-managed campsites that offer cheap tent pitches, basic toilets, and quiet sand. The crowds are smaller than Zambales and the access is easier from Manila via TPLEX.</p>
<p>This is the calm slow roundup. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>Patar White Beach (Bolinao)</h2>
<p>Patar is the headline beach on the Bolinao peninsula. The sand is fine and white, the water is clear, and the headland separates the beach into two coves. Camping is allowed at the public section near the small lighthouse; the barangay collects a small fee (around 100 pesos per pitch). Toilets are basic but functional.</p>
<p>The beach is busiest on weekends from December to May. Weekdays are calmer. The sunset is the famous one; the headland frames the South China Sea horizon.</p>
<h2>Tara Beach (Bolinao)</h2>
<p>Tara is a smaller cove north of Patar, with a quieter atmosphere and a more local crowd. The sand is similar to Patar but the beach is shorter (around 400 meters). The small camping ground at the south end has tent pads and shared toilets.</p>
<p>The reef offshore is good for snorkeling; bring your own mask and snorkel.</p>
<h2>Anda Beach (Anda)</h2>
<p>Anda is on the northwest coast of Pangasinan, around 45 minutes by tricycle from Bolinao. The beach is wide and the sand is golden rather than white. The small barangay campsite at the south end has basic facilities.</p>
<p>Anda is the calmer alternative to Patar with a more remote feel. The waves are slightly bigger here.</p>
<h2>Lucap Wharf Camping (Alaminos)</h2>
<p>Lucap Wharf is the launching point for the Hundred Islands. The small grass campsite near the wharf is for travelers who want an early-morning start to the islands. The pitch is around 100 to 200 pesos and the toilets are at the wharf compound.</p>
<p>The camping is not on a beach in the strict sense; the wharf overlooks a small bay. Use it as a logistics base, not a destination camp.</p>
<h2>Hundred Islands (Alaminos)</h2>
<p>Selected islands in the Hundred Islands group allow overnight camping with a permit from the local management office. The popular camping islands are Quezon Island, Governor Island, and Children's Island. The pitch fee is around 200 to 400 pesos plus the entrance and boat fees.</p>
<p>Bring your own tent and water. The islands have basic shared toilets but no electricity beyond the limited solar lights at Quezon Island.</p>
<h2>Bolinao Falls Side Camping (Bolinao)</h2>
<p>The area around Bolinao Falls 1 and Falls 2 has small barangay camping grounds for backpackers who want to do the falls in the morning and the beach in the afternoon. The pitch fee is around 100 to 150 pesos and the toilets are basic.</p>
<p>This is the freshwater camping option; the falls swim is the morning activity.</p>
<h2>Tondol Beach (Anda)</h2>
<p>Tondol is the long shallow beach in Anda where the water stays knee-deep for hundreds of meters offshore. The shallow zone is the unique feature; at low tide the walk-out extends almost a kilometer. Camping is allowed at the public section near the entrance.</p>
<p>The shallow water makes Tondol the kid-friendly beach option. Bring water shoes; the seagrass and the small shells are the trade-off.</p>
<h2>Cabongaoan Beach (Burgos)</h2>
<p>Cabongaoan is the rocky cove beach in Burgos, between Bolinao and Anda. The famous "death pool" (a natural saltwater pool carved into the rock platform) is the photo draw. Camping is allowed on the small grass area above the rocks.</p>
<p>The beach is not a swimming beach in the conventional sense; the rocks and the strong current make swimming risky. The death pool is the calm controlled swim spot.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<p>A proper tent (sea breeze on the western coast can be strong), a sleeping mat, a quick-dry towel, a headlamp, drinking water (one to two liters per person for an overnight), a small camp stove if you cook (gas canisters are easy to find in Bolinao town), reef-safe sunscreen, insect repellent, and trash bags for carry-out.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry, calm window with the cleanest sand and the easiest camping. June through October is the rainy season; some campsites close for the typhoon months.</p>
<p>Pangasinan beach camping is the calm budget alternative to Zambales. Sulit for the patient traveler with the right gear.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Pangasinan Beach Campsites: Calm Slow Roundup | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm slow roundup of Pangasinan beach campsites from Bolinao to Anda, with notes on Patar, Tondol, Cabongaoan, Hundred Islands, and what to bring.',
        'tags' => 'Pangasinan, Beach Camping, Bolinao, Anda, Patar',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'bolinao',
    ],

    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 30. BOLINAO FALLS 1 2 3 CASCADE CHAIN DAY
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://wanderera.com/things-to-do-in-bolinao/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Wander Era',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Bolinao Falls 1, 2, and 3: A Calm Cascade Chain Day',
        'slug' => 'bolinao-falls-1-2-3-calm-cascade-chain-day',
        'excerpt' => 'Bolinao has three numbered cascades within a 20-minute drive of town. Here is the calm one-day chain visit read.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Bolinao has three numbered waterfalls scattered within a 20-minute tricycle ride of the town center. They are called simply Bolinao Falls 1, Bolinao Falls 2, and Bolinao Falls 3, and each has a different character: Falls 1 has the classic three-tier cascade and rope swing, Falls 2 has the wider swimming pool with the cool jungle setting, and Falls 3 has the small intimate cascade with the deeper pool.</p>
<p>This is a calm one-day chain read. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>How to Get There</h2>
<p>From Bolinao town center, a tricycle to the falls cluster runs around 400 to 600 pesos round trip with wait time at each falls. The drivers know the standard chain order: Falls 1, then 2, then 3, or in reverse depending on the road condition.</p>
<p>A scooter rental (around 350 pesos for a day) is the cheaper and more flexible option. The roads to the falls are paved but narrow.</p>
<h2>Bolinao Falls 1</h2>
<p>Falls 1 is the most popular of the three. It has a three-tier cascade with a wide swimming pool at the base, a small rope swing tied to a tree at the side, and a low cliff (around three meters) for jumping. The water is cool year-round and the pool is around two to three meters deep at the center.</p>
<p>Entrance fee is around 30 to 50 pesos. The trail from the parking area to the falls is a 200-meter walk on a paved path. The crowds peak on weekends from 10 a.m. to 2 p.m.; arrive before 9 a.m. for the calm window.</p>
<h2>Bolinao Falls 2</h2>
<p>Falls 2 is about 10 minutes by tricycle from Falls 1. It has a single 15-meter cascade with a wider swimming pool than Falls 1, surrounded by jungle and tall trees. The setting feels more remote; the trail in is a 300-meter walk on a dirt path through small farms.</p>
<p>Entrance fee is around 30 to 50 pesos. The crowds are smaller here than at Falls 1; weekday visits often find the pool half-empty. The jumping cliff is higher than at Falls 1 (around five meters); the brave can jump but check the pool depth first.</p>
<h2>Bolinao Falls 3</h2>
<p>Falls 3 is the smallest and most intimate of the three. It has a single eight-meter cascade with a small deep pool surrounded by limestone rocks. The setting is quieter than the other two and the crowd is smallest.</p>
<p>Entrance fee is around 30 pesos. The trail in is a short 150-meter walk. The pool is around three to four meters deep, deeper than its size suggests. The cliff jump from the side rocks is around four meters.</p>
<h2>The Chain Order</h2>
<p>The standard chain order is Falls 1 first (since it is the closest to town and the most popular), then Falls 2, then Falls 3. The reverse order is also fine; arriving at Falls 3 first lets you experience the smallest before the bigger two.</p>
<p>Total time for the full chain is four to five hours including the tricycle rides, the trail walks, and the swims at each falls. A full half-day from 8 a.m. to 1 p.m. fits the chain comfortably.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<p>Swim clothes, a quick-dry towel, a dry bag for valuables, water shoes (the trails and the pool edges are wet), reef-safe sunscreen, drinking water, a packed lunch or cash for the small canteens at each falls, a power bank, and a waterproof phone case.</p>
<h2>The Tip</h2>
<p>Pair the falls chain with a sunset stop at Patar Beach (15 minutes from Falls 3). The morning chain at the falls leaves the afternoon free for the beach. This is the standard Bolinao first-day plan.</p>
<p>For the second day, do the Hundred Islands tour (one hour from Bolinao to the Alaminos wharf) or the Bolinao town circuit (Capilla, Cape Bolinao Lighthouse, Enchanted Cave).</p>
<h2>The Etiquette</h2>
<p>The falls are barangay-managed and the cleanliness depends on visitor cooperation. Carry out your trash. Do not bring single-use plastic if you can avoid it. Do not use shampoo or soap in the pools; the water flows downstream to the local farms.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry, warm window with the easiest swimming weather. June through October is the rainy season; the falls are at their fullest but the water can be murky and the trails are muddy.</p>
<p>The Bolinao falls chain is the calm freshwater alternative to the Patar beach day. Sulit for the patient traveler who chains the three in one slow morning.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Bolinao Falls 1, 2, and 3: Calm Cascade Chain Day | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm one-day read on the three Bolinao numbered waterfalls, with the swimming pools, the rope swings, the chain order, and what to bring.',
        'tags' => 'Bolinao Falls, Pangasinan, Waterfall, Day Trip, Cascade',
