    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 31. BOLINAO 16 STOPS SLOW WEST COAST DAY
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://wanderera.com/things-to-do-in-bolinao/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Wander Era',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Bolinao Slow West Coast: A Calm Two-Day Stop List',
        'slug' => 'bolinao-slow-west-coast-calm-two-day-stop-list',
        'excerpt' => 'Bolinao has more than just Patar Beach. Here is the calm two-day stop list for the patient west-coast traveler.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Bolinao sits on the tip of the western Pangasinan peninsula, about six to seven hours by bus from Manila via TPLEX. Most travelers do Bolinao as a quick Patar Beach overnight; the patient traveler who stretches it to two days finds a town with limestone caves, a 17th-century stone church, an old lighthouse, a marine laboratory, and three numbered waterfalls.</p>
<p>This is a calm two-day stop list. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>Day One Morning: Saint James Church (Bolinao)</h2>
<p>The Saint James the Great Church in Bolinao town center dates to 1609, making it one of the oldest stone churches in northwest Luzon. The walls are made of coral stone quarried from the local shoreline and the facade still shows the original baroque carvings. Entry is free; modest dress code applies.</p>
<p>Adjacent to the church is the Bolinao town plaza and the small museum that holds local artifacts from the pre-Spanish period and the Spanish colonial era. The museum is small (one to two hours to see fully) and the entrance fee is modest.</p>
<h2>Day One Late Morning: Cape Bolinao Lighthouse</h2>
<p>The Cape Bolinao Lighthouse is on the cape headland, around 30 minutes by tricycle west of the town center. The lighthouse dates to 1905 and is one of the highest in the country, standing 351 meters above sea level on the rocky cliff. The climb to the top of the lighthouse tower is around 134 steps; the view from the gallery is the South China Sea on three sides.</p>
<p>Entry is free. The lighthouse compound is open during daylight hours; the keeper opens the tower stairs on request.</p>
<h2>Day One Afternoon: Patar Beach</h2>
<p>After the lighthouse, ride down to Patar Beach (10 minutes from the lighthouse). The beach is the famous white-sand stretch with a rocky headland in the middle that divides it into two coves. Swim, walk the beach, and stay for the sunset; the cape headland frames the South China Sea horizon at dusk.</p>
<p>For the late afternoon, try the small carinderia at the south end of Patar for a fresh grilled fish lunch. The catch is from the local fishermen earlier the same morning.</p>
<h2>Day Two Morning: Enchanted Cave</h2>
<p>The Enchanted Cave is on the road between Bolinao town and Patar Beach, around 20 minutes by tricycle. The cave is a small limestone formation with a clear freshwater pool inside the chamber and a few stalactite formations. The entrance fee is around 200 pesos and the small dressing room is at the entrance.</p>
<p>The swim in the pool is the unique experience; the water is cold even at midday and the chamber lighting is soft. Allow 30 to 45 minutes for the visit.</p>
<h2>Day Two Mid-Morning: Wonderful Cave and Cindy Cave</h2>
<p>Adjacent to Enchanted Cave are two smaller caves with similar pool features. Wonderful Cave has a small pool with a higher cliff edge; Cindy Cave has a narrower chamber with a deeper pool. Both have small entrance fees (around 100 pesos each) and basic facilities.</p>
<p>If you have done Enchanted, the other two are diminishing returns; pick one as a backup.</p>
<h2>Day Two Late Morning: Bolinao Falls 1 and 2</h2>
<p>Ride to Bolinao Falls 1 (15 minutes from the cave area). The three-tier cascade and the rope swing are the headline draw. Swim, then ride to Falls 2 (10 minutes from Falls 1) for the wider pool and the jungle setting. See the longer cascade chain guide for details.</p>
<h2>Day Two Afternoon: UP Marine Lab</h2>
<p>The UP Marine Science Institute Bolinao Marine Laboratory is on the coast near Patar. The lab is open to public visitors with a small guided tour fee (around 150 pesos). The tour covers the giant clam nursery, the seagrass research area, and the coral propagation tanks.</p>
<p>The visit is educational and the staff are friendly. The lab is a working research facility; the visit hours and the guided tour days are limited. Call ahead to confirm.</p>
<h2>Day Two Sunset: Cape Bolinao Lighthouse Sunset</h2>
<p>End the two-day trip with the lighthouse sunset. Climb the tower one more time for the dusk view; the keeper usually allows late visits if you ask politely. The light at the gallery during the golden hour is the best photo of the trip.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<p>Swim clothes, a quick-dry towel, a dry bag for valuables, water shoes for the falls and the caves, reef-safe sunscreen, insect repellent, drinking water, snacks, cash for the multiple entrance fees and tricycle rides.</p>
<h2>Getting Around</h2>
<p>A scooter rental (around 350 to 500 pesos per day) is the most flexible way to do the two-day plan. The roads are paved but narrow. A tricycle for the full day (around 1,500 to 2,000 pesos) is the alternative if you prefer not to drive.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat</h2>
<p>For breakfast, the small carinderias along the Bolinao town center serve longganisa or tapsilog with rice (around 100 pesos). For lunch, the Patar Beach grills serve fresh fish. For dinner, the small Bolinao town restaurants have local Pangasinan specialties: pigar-pigar (Dagupan-style beef stir-fry), bagoong rice, and inihaw na bangus.</p>
<p>For pasalubong, buy the Bolinao bagoong (fermented fish paste) and the local salted fish at the public market.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry, warm window with the cleanest beach water and the easiest road conditions. June through October is the rainy season; the falls are at their fullest but the beach can be choppy.</p>
<p>Bolinao is the calm two-day west-coast trip that rewards the patient traveler. Sulit for the slow planner.</p>
