    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 32. MOALBOAL SEVEN THINGS BEYOND THE SARDINES
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://wanderera.com/things-to-do-in-moalboal/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Wander Era',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Moalboal Seven Things Beyond the Sardines: A Calm Read',
        'slug' => 'moalboal-seven-things-beyond-sardines-calm-read',
        'excerpt' => 'Moalboal is famous for the sardine run but the town has six other slow stops worth a calm day. Here is the read.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Moalboal sits on the west coast of Cebu, about three hours by bus from Cebu City. The town is famous for the sardine run at Panagsama Beach (where dense schools of millions of sardines swim close to shore year-round), but the area has more than just the snorkel headline. The patient traveler who stays two or three days finds a small beach base with diving, canyoneering, turtle encounters, a quieter beach, and a slower town pace.</p>
<p>This is a calm seven-stop read. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>1. The Sardine Run at Panagsama</h2>
<p>The sardines have made Panagsama their year-round home; you do not need a boat to see them. Walk into the water from the seawall at the south end of the beach, swim out 20 to 30 meters, and the school will be there. The visibility is best between 9 a.m. and noon.</p>
<p>Bring your own snorkel set or rent at the beach (around 150 pesos). Reef-safe sunscreen is mandatory; the local diveshop community has made this a serious advisory.</p>
<h2>2. The Diving</h2>
<p>Moalboal has 20 to 30 dive shops along the Panagsama Road and the diving is the second draw after the sardines. Pescador Island is the marquee site (around 20 minutes by banca, with steep wall diving and frequent thresher and reef shark sightings on the deeper edges). The shore dives along Panagsama are good for refresher dives and night dives.</p>
<p>Standard PADI Open Water courses run in three to four days. Day-trip fun dives are around 1,500 to 2,500 pesos for a two-tank guided dive.</p>
<h2>3. Kawasan Canyoneering</h2>
<p>Kawasan Falls is in the next town (Badian), 30 minutes south of Moalboal. The standard activity is canyoneering: a four-hour guided trip that combines jumps, swims, and slides down the Matutinao River to the falls. Multiple operators run the trips out of Moalboal.</p>
<p>The activity is moderately physical and the jumps range from two to 15 meters. See the existing Kawasan canyoneering guide for the full pacing.</p>
<h2>4. Turtle Encounters at Pescador or Talisay</h2>
<p>The Pescador Island circuit includes a high-probability turtle sighting at the small reef on the southwest side. Green sea turtles and the rare hawksbills are commonly seen at three to six meters depth. The Talisay Beach (15 minutes by tricycle from Panagsama) also has regular turtle sightings in the shallow grass beds.</p>
<p>Snorkel rules apply: do not chase, do not touch, do not block the turtle's surface path.</p>
<h2>5. White Beach</h2>
<p>The Moalboal locals call this small beach "White Beach" or "Basdaku" to distinguish it from the rocky Panagsama. White Beach is a 15-minute tricycle ride north of Panagsama. The sand is fine and white, the water is shallow and calm, and the beach is the family-friendly alternative to the dive-shop strip at Panagsama.</p>
<p>The beach is busiest on weekends; weekdays are calmer.</p>
<h2>6. Lambug Beach</h2>
<p>Lambug Beach is in Badian, 30 minutes south of Moalboal. It is a longer, quieter beach than White Beach and the local crowd is mostly families. The water is shallow and the sand is fine. Small camping is allowed at the public section near the entrance.</p>
<p>Lambug is the slow alternative to the busier Moalboal beaches. The locals barbecue here on Sundays.</p>
<h2>7. Osmena Peak (Day Trip)</h2>
<p>Osmena Peak is the highest point in Cebu at 1,013 meters above sea level. It is a 30-minute habal-habal ride from Mantalongon Market in Dalaguete (one hour by bus from Moalboal). The hike from the parking area to the summit is 20 to 30 minutes on a clear marked trail.</p>
<p>The view from the summit covers the central Cebu spine of hills (the local nickname is "Cebu's Chocolate Hills"). Sunrise hikes are popular with early-leaving groups from Moalboal.</p>
<h2>Where to Eat</h2>
<p>Moalboal has a small but diverse food scene at Panagsama. The Yellow Brick Road has a quiet pizzeria. Last Filling Station is the breakfast institution with a wide menu. Three Bears Bakery serves the best croissants in the area. For local Cebuano, the small carinderias along the Panagsama Road serve lechon, kinilaw, and grilled fish.</p>
<h2>Getting Around</h2>
<p>Tricycles within Panagsama and to White Beach are around 50 to 100 pesos. Habal-habal motorbikes for the longer rides (Lambug, Osmena) are around 100 to 200 pesos. A scooter rental (around 350 pesos a day) is the flexible option.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry, calm window with the best dive visibility and the warmest snorkel water. June through October is the rainy season; the sardines are still there but the visibility drops.</p>
<p>Moalboal is the calm Cebu base for travelers who want to slow down. Sulit for the patient diver and the patient snorkeler.</p>
