    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    // 35. MT GULUGOD BABOY SECOND-TIME SUNSET VARIANT
    // ------------------------------------------------------------------
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://wanderera.com/things-to-do-in-batangas/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Wander Era',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Mt Gulugod Baboy Sunset Variant: A Calm Second-Time Hike',
        'slug' => 'mt-gulugod-baboy-sunset-variant-calm-second-time-hike',
        'excerpt' => 'Mt Gulugod Baboy in Mabini is usually a sunrise hike. Here is the calm sunset variant for the second-time climber.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Mt Gulugod Baboy in Mabini, Batangas is one of the most popular day hikes from Manila. The summit at 525 meters above sea level looks down on the Anilao dive coast and the Verde Island Passage. Most first-time climbers do the standard sunrise variant: leave Manila at midnight, arrive at the trailhead by 3 a.m., summit by 4:30 a.m., catch the sunrise.</p>
<p>The patient traveler who has already done the sunrise hike can come back for the calmer sunset variant. This is the kwento.</p>
<h2>The Sunrise vs Sunset Difference</h2>
<p>The sunrise hike is the busy one. The trail is full by 4 a.m. with school groups, hike clubs, and weekend bargaining barkadas. The summit is crowded with 100 to 200 climbers on a popular weekend. The light is dramatic but the experience is loud.</p>
<p>The sunset hike is the quiet one. The trail is half-empty at 4 p.m. The summit holds 20 to 40 climbers, mostly couples and small barkadas. The light is softer and the descent through the dusk is the slower experience.</p>
<h2>The Trail</h2>
<p>The trail starts at the small Philpan Dive Resort area in Anilao, where the trail registration is. From the registration, the trail climbs through cogon grass and small forest sections for around two hours at a slow pace. The grade is moderate; the trail is wide enough for two-way traffic.</p>
<p>The trail forks at the small saddle. The right fork goes to the main summit (Mt Gulugod Baboy proper). The left fork goes to the secondary Pinagbanderahan peak (slightly lower, with a different angle on the bay).</p>
<h2>The Sunset Timing</h2>
<p>For a 6:00 p.m. sunset in November, leave the trailhead by 3:30 p.m. The summit ascent takes around two hours at a comfortable pace; you arrive by 5:30 p.m. with 30 minutes for the photos and the rest before the light goes.</p>
<p>For a 6:30 p.m. sunset in March, the same logic applies; adjust the start time by 30 minutes.</p>
<h2>The Descent</h2>
<p>The descent in the dusk is the part that needs care. Bring a headlamp. The trail is well-marked but the cogon grass sections look different in the low light. Plan for the descent to take 90 minutes to two hours at a slow pace.</p>
<p>The full sunset-and-descent variant runs from 3:30 p.m. trailhead arrival to 7:30 p.m. trailhead departure. The barkada dinner in Anilao or Mabini town center fits naturally after.</p>
<h2>The Summit View</h2>
<p>The summit view covers the Verde Island Passage to the south, the Anilao dive coast to the west, the Tingloy Island in the middle, and the Mindoro coastline on the far horizon. The sunset behind Tingloy Island is the iconic photo. On the clearest evenings, the silhouette of Mt Calavite on northwest Mindoro is visible against the dusk sky.</p>
<h2>The Etiquette</h2>
<p>Gulugod Baboy is a popular mountain and the local trail registration runs on a small budget. Pay the fee (around 30 pesos for day use), respect the trail markers, and carry out your trash.</p>
<p>The trail has small camp areas for overnight stays. If you camp, the rules tighten: no open fires, no loud music, no leaving anything behind.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<p>Trail runners or hiking shoes, a light jacket for the descent, a headlamp (mandatory for the sunset variant), drinking water (two liters per person), a small snack, sunscreen and a hat for the climb (the cogon sections are unshaded), a small first-aid kit, and a small trash bag.</p>
<h2>How to Get There</h2>
<p>From Manila, take a Jam Liner bus from Cubao or Buendia to Batangas City Grand Terminal. Fare is around 200 pesos and the trip is two to three hours. From the terminal, take a jeepney to Anilao Port (around 50 pesos, one hour) or a taxi to the trailhead (around 400 to 500 pesos).</p>
<h2>Pair It With</h2>
<p>Pair the sunset hike with an early-afternoon snorkel at one of the Anilao dive sites (Bahura, Cathedral Rock, or the closer house reefs). The full day fits: morning snorkel, late lunch, sunset hike, dinner in Mabini.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry, clear window with the most reliable sunset light. June through October is the rainy season; the trail is muddy and the summit is often in cloud.</p>
<p>The Mt Gulugod Baboy sunset variant is the calm second-time read for the patient climber. Sulit for the slow-paced barkada.</p>
HTML,
        'meta_title' => 'Mt Gulugod Baboy Sunset Variant: Calm Hike | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm sunset variant for the second-time Mt Gulugod Baboy climber in Mabini, Batangas, with the trail, the timing, and the dusk descent.',
        'tags' => 'Mt Gulugod Baboy, Mabini, Batangas, Sunset Hike, Anilao',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'anilao-mabini',
