        'excerpt' => 'Pansol in Calamba has 100+ private hot spring rentals. Here is the calm honest read on how to pick and what to expect.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Pansol is a small barangay in Calamba, Laguna, about 1.5 to 2 hours south of Manila on the SLEX. The barangay sits at the base of Mt Makiling and the natural hot springs that bubble up from the volcanic ground have made Pansol the densest cluster of private hot spring rentals in the country. Over 100 small resorts offer day-use and overnight rentals of small pool houses with their own private hot spring pool.</p>
<p>This is the calm honest read on how to pick. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>The Format</h2>
<p>Most Pansol resorts follow the same format: a private compound with one to three pool houses, each house has a small private hot spring pool (typically two to four meters wide, 1.2 to 1.5 meters deep), a small dirty kitchen with a grill, a covered dining area, basic shower and toilet, and a small living area.</p>
<p>The rental is whole-house for a barkada or family. The capacity ranges from six to 20 depending on the size. We do not list rates here; book directly with the operator.</p>
<h2>The Water</h2>
<p>The hot spring water in Pansol comes from natural underground sources fed by the geothermal activity of Mt Makiling. The water temperature at the source ranges from 38 to 42 degrees Celsius. The pool temperature ranges from 35 to 40 depending on how recently the water was refilled.</p>
<p>The water is mineral-rich with sulfur, calcium, and magnesium. It is safe to swim in but not safe to drink. Pregnant women, people with heart conditions, and small infants should consult a doctor before extended soaks. Limit each soak session to 20 to 30 minutes; alternate with breaks at room temperature.</p>
<h2>How to Pick a Resort</h2>
<p>The resorts are clustered along the main Pansol road (the Old Highway and several connecting streets). The differences are in the pool size, the cleanliness of the facilities, the kitchen quality, and the surrounding noise level.</p>
<p>For a quiet family stay, pick a resort at the back of the compound clusters or one with a larger compound that separates the pool houses. For a party-style barkada night, the front-cluster resorts are more flexible with later noise.</p>
<p>Read recent reviews on Facebook or Google. Photos on the booking pages can be five to ten years old; verify the current state with a phone call to the operator.</p>
<h2>The Family-Friendly Picks</h2>
<p>For young families, the key features to look for:</p>
<ul>
<li>A small shallow pool section (the local term is "kiddie pool") for small children.</li>
<li>A covered dining area with mosquito screens.</li>
<li>A grilled-area kitchen that allows you to bring your own food.</li>
<li>A 24-hour caretaker or security.</li>
<li>Distance from the noisier roads.</li>
</ul>
<p>Pansol is a family-tradition destination for many Manila families. The Sunday day-use slots fill up fastest.</p>
<h2>The Food</h2>
<p>Most Pansol rentals are BYO food. The dirty kitchen has a grill, a counter, basic utensils, and (sometimes) a small refrigerator. Bring your own marinated meats, charcoal, snacks, and drinks.</p>
<p>For travelers who do not cook, the small carinderias along the Pansol road serve grilled meals and rice for around 200 to 350 pesos per plate. A few resorts offer in-house cooking for an extra fee.</p>
<h2>How to Get There</h2>
<p>From Manila, take a JAC Liner or DLTB bus from Cubao or Buendia to Calamba. Fare is around 100 to 150 pesos and the trip is 1.5 to 2 hours. From the Calamba terminal, take a tricycle or jeepney to Pansol (around 15 to 20 minutes, 50 to 80 pesos).</p>
<p>If you drive, exit SLEX at Calamba, then follow the small signs to Pansol. Parking is at the resort compound.</p>
<h2>The Etiquette</h2>
<p>Pansol is a working barangay with permanent residents. Keep the music at reasonable volume. Do not park along the small barangay roads (use the resort parking). Do not bring single-use plastic in large quantities; the local waste management is limited.</p>
<p>Carry out your trash or leave it at the resort designated bin. The caretaker handles disposal.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through February is the cool-dry window where the hot pool feels best (the ambient air is cooler, the contrast is real). March through May is the warm window where the hot pool feels less special but the resorts are busy with summer break. June through October is the rainy season; the resorts are open year-round.</p>
<p>Avoid Holy Week and Labor Day for spontaneous bookings; the resorts are fully booked weeks ahead.</p>
<p>Pansol is the calm family hot spring tradition close to Manila. Sulit for the patient traveler who picks the right resort.</p>
