        'excerpt' => 'The 2GO Batangas to Caticlan overnight ferry is the calm sea route to Boracay. Here is the honest read on the schedule and the ride.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>The 2GO Batangas to Caticlan ferry is the overnight sea route from Luzon to the Aklan gateway of Boracay. The trip is around 10 to 11 hours overnight, the cabin is reserved, and the arrival in Caticlan is timed for an early-morning crossing to Boracay. The route is the slower and cheaper alternative to the Manila to Caticlan flight, especially for travelers who want to save a hotel night by sleeping on the ferry.</p>
<p>This is the calm honest read. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>The Operator</h2>
<p>2GO Travel runs the Batangas to Caticlan overnight route on its St. Therese of the Child Jesus and similar vessels. The ferry is a multi-class ship with economy, tourist, cabin, and suite classes. The frequency is around three to four departures per week, mostly in the evening (around 9 to 10 p.m.).</p>
<p>The route runs only when sea conditions allow. During the typhoon months (June to October), the route is sometimes paused; check the 2GO website or call the Batangas terminal for the current schedule.</p>
<h2>The Schedule</h2>
<p>The standard departure from the Batangas Pier is around 10 p.m. The arrival in Caticlan is around 8 to 9 a.m. the next morning. The return trip from Caticlan to Batangas leaves at around 8 to 9 p.m. and arrives in Batangas at around 7 to 8 a.m. the next morning.</p>
<p>The exact departure days shift seasonally. Common departures are Tuesday, Friday, and Sunday for the Batangas to Caticlan leg; the return runs on different days.</p>
<h2>The Fare</h2>
<p>2GO has a tiered fare structure. The economy fare (open-air bunks on the lower deck) is the cheapest at around 800 to 1,200 pesos. The tourist class (small enclosed bunks) is around 1,500 to 2,000 pesos. The cabin class (private rooms with two to four bunks) is around 3,000 to 5,000 pesos per person. The suite is around 6,000 to 10,000 pesos.</p>
<p>The cabin class is the recommended pick for first-time overnight travelers. The privacy and the cleaner sleeping conditions justify the higher fare.</p>
<h2>How to Get to the Batangas Pier</h2>
<p>From Manila, take a Jam Liner or Jac Liner bus from Cubao, Buendia, or Pasay to the Batangas City Grand Terminal. Fare is around 200 pesos and the trip is two to three hours. From the terminal, take a tricycle or jeepney to the Batangas Pier (around 15 minutes, 50 pesos).</p>
<p>Arrive at the pier two hours before departure for the check-in, the terminal fee, and the boarding. The terminal fee is around 30 to 50 pesos.</p>
<h2>The Onboard Experience</h2>
<p>The economy and tourist classes are on the lower decks with shared bunks and shared bathrooms. The cabin classes are on the upper decks with private rooms, individual bunks, and shared deck access.</p>
<p>The ferry has a small dining hall, a canteen with basic Filipino meals, and a small convenience store. The food on board is basic; many travelers bring their own snacks.</p>
<p>The deck is open for the duration of the trip. The sea views are the calm slow part of the journey.</p>
<h2>What to Pack</h2>
<p>A small overnight bag with sleeping essentials. A light sweater (the cabin air-conditioning is set cold). A sleep mask and earplugs (the cabin can be noisy). A small toiletry kit. Snacks and drinking water. A power bank (the cabin has one outlet per room). Motion sickness pills if you are prone (the Tablas Strait crossing can be rough on windy nights).</p>
<h2>The Caticlan Arrival</h2>
<p>The ferry docks at the Caticlan Jetty Port. Walk off, claim your luggage at the porter station, then walk to the adjacent Boracay-bound banca terminal. The Boracay crossing is 15 to 20 minutes on a small banca. The Caticlan terminal fee plus the Boracay environmental fee adds around 200 to 300 pesos to the trip.</p>
<p>The Boracay-bound banca arrival is at Caticlan-bound Cagban Port on Boracay. From there, a tricycle takes you to your accommodation along the beach strip.</p>
<h2>The Return</h2>
<p>The return Boracay to Batangas runs on the same logic in reverse. Leave Boracay by mid-afternoon for the Caticlan banca, the Caticlan terminal, and the 8 p.m. boarding. Arrive Batangas by 7 a.m. the next morning. The return is the calmer leg because the Boracay departure is in daylight.</p>
<h2>The Tip</h2>
<p>If you have not done an overnight ferry before, treat the trip as part of the experience. Bring a book or a downloaded series. The sunrise at sea on the Caticlan approach is the calm reward of the trip.</p>
<p>2GO Batangas to Caticlan is the calm slow sea route to Boracay. Sulit for the patient traveler who books the cabin class.</p>
