        'excerpt' => 'Caohagan Island off Mactan is the small handicraft and quilt community. Here is the calm half-day boat read.',
        'content_html' => <<<'HTML'
<p>Caohagan Island sits off the south coast of Mactan, around 30 to 45 minutes by banca from the Mactan piers. The island is small (around 1.3 hectares, walkable in 15 minutes end to end) and the resident population is around 600 to 700 people, mostly fisher families. The island earned its name in the wider travel circuit not for the beach but for the handmade quilt community that has been stitching colorful Mactan-style quilts for decades.</p>
<p>This is the calm half-day read on the handicraft side. Tara, the kwento.</p>
<h2>The Quilt Community</h2>
<p>Caohagan has a small but active women's handicraft cooperative that produces traditional Mactan-style hand-stitched quilts. The quilts are made from cotton scraps in vivid color combinations, hand-stitched in geometric patterns that follow generational designs. The cooperative was supported by a Japanese cultural initiative in the 1990s and the quality of the work is recognized internationally.</p>
<p>Each quilt takes weeks to finish. The price reflects the labor; a small wall hanging is around 1,500 to 3,000 pesos and a large bed-size quilt is around 6,000 to 15,000 pesos. The cooperative also produces smaller items: pillow covers, table runners, small purses.</p>
<h2>The Visit</h2>
<p>Most island-hopping tours from Mactan include Caohagan as a stop, but the standard tour gives only 30 to 45 minutes on the island. For the patient traveler who wants the slow handicraft side, book a private banca for the day or a small-group tour that allows two to three hours on the island.</p>
<p>On arrival, the small boatmen will direct you to the cooperative workshop near the small beach. Walk in, watch the women stitching (mornings are the active hours), browse the finished pieces, ask questions. The cooperative members speak basic English and the Cebuano-speaking ones are happy to explain the patterns.</p>
<h2>The Island Walk</h2>
<p>The island is small enough to walk in 15 to 20 minutes. The path circles the small village. The houses are mostly bamboo and concrete, the small chapel sits at the center, and the small grade school is on the south side.</p>
<p>The walk shows the daily life of a small Mactan fishing community: women cleaning fish, kids playing badminton, men repairing nets, dogs sleeping in the shade. The slow walk is the calm contrast to the busy Cebu City or Lapu-Lapu strips.</p>
<h2>The Beach</h2>
<p>The small beach on the north side of the island is the main swimming area. The sand is fine, the water is shallow and calm, and the snorkeling at the small reef offshore is decent. The beach is busiest when an island-hopping group is there (around midday); the morning and the late afternoon are calmer.</p>
<p>Bring your own snorkel set if you can; the rentals on the island are limited.</p>
<h2>The Food</h2>
<p>The cooperative members and a few local families run small lunch services for visiting groups. The standard menu is the famous Caohagan grilled fish, rice, kinilaw (raw fish in vinegar and coconut), seaweed salad, and a fresh fruit dessert. The seafood is from the local fishermen earlier the same morning; the freshness is the main draw.</p>
<p>A lunch for a small group is around 500 to 800 pesos per person. The portions are generous and the cooking is home-style. The food alone is sometimes the reason travelers come back.</p>
<h2>How to Get There</h2>
<p>The bancas to Caohagan leave from the Maribago Bay or the Hilutungan Bay pier on Mactan. A private banca for the half-day or full day is around 2,500 to 4,500 pesos for a small boat (capacity six to eight). A shared island-hopping tour that includes Caohagan and one or two other islands (Nalusuan, Hilutungan) is around 1,500 to 2,500 pesos per person.</p>
<p>From the Cebu airport or the city, a taxi or Grab to the Maribago piers takes around 30 minutes.</p>
<h2>What to Bring</h2>
<p>Swim clothes, a quick-dry towel, reef-safe sunscreen, a rash guard, drinking water, a hat, sunglasses, cash for the cooperative purchases and the lunch, a small dry bag for valuables. A waterproof camera or a phone case.</p>
<h2>The Etiquette</h2>
<p>Caohagan is a small residential community, not a public beach. Show respect: ask permission before photographing the local people, do not leave trash on the island, do not bring large groups without notice. The cooperative is generous with visitors but the community life is the priority.</p>
<p>Buying a quilt is the meaningful way to support the cooperative. Even a small purchase (a coin purse, a wall hanging) covers a real-cost contribution to the family stitcher.</p>
<h2>When to Go</h2>
<p>December through May is the dry, calm window with the smoothest sea crossing. June through October is the rainy season; the bancas still run on calm days but the crossings can be choppy.</p>
<p>Caohagan is the calm small-island day with a real handicraft tradition. Sulit for the patient traveler who books a longer stop.</p>
